<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     08-20 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Head Hails Court Ruling on Hiring Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a federal employees union says a
federal appeals court ruling will force the Reagan administration
to replace a civil service test that was found to discriminate
against minorities.
   The Office of Personnel Management ``can no longer ignore their
obligation to develop an alternative system,'' National Treasury
Employees Union President Robert Tobias said Friday following the
ruling by the U.S. Court of Appeals.
   The three-judged panel ruled that OPM acted ``arbitrarily and
capriciously'' in not providing figures to back its claim that high
costs rule out developing a new test for filling entry-level jobs.
   Because the old test was found to be biased earlier in the
long-running court dispute, the agency has been using a
non-competitive hiring system based on grades and performance in
interviews. OPM spokesman Dick McGowan said the agency would have
no comment on the ruling.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Recall Ordered for More Than 22,000 Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 22,000 heavy trucks are being
recalled because of potential defects in power steering gears that
could result in ``sudden and catastrophic failure,'' the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration says.
   The TRW Ross Gear division, which produced the steering gears,
and manufacturers of Peterbilt, Kenworth, Freightliner, Western
Star and White GMC trucks, urged that affected trucks be removed
from highways immediately and towed to the nearest truck dealer,
the agency said Friday.
   The recall affects 22,687 trucks carrying certain steering gears
manufactured by TRW Ross Gear division since last March. The safety
agency said TRW has confirmed seven incidents of steering gear
failure since June.
   The agency said the suspect equipment includes certain TRW Ross
Gear division TAS-65 truck steering gears sold for production and a
limited number of TAS-65, TAS-40 and TAS-55 gears sold as
prototypes. The TAS-65 gears have date codes of 085-88 or higher
and were shipped after March 24.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Asked to Block Lawn Darts Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal commission says Sears Roebuck and
Co. has continued to sell lawn darts in violation of a promise to
stop marketing the allegedly hazardous game.
   The Consumer Products Safety Commission filed suit Friday in
U.S. District Court here, asking that Sears be found in contempt
and be ordered to halt sales of the horseshoes-like game in which
darts are thrown at targets on the ground.
   ``I'm disappointed at Sears for this new violation but expect
this contempt action will send a strong message to Sears and other
retailers that the CPSC will enforce its regulations on lawn
darts,'' said Commission Chairman Terrence M. Scanlon.
   Sears headquarters in Chicago said in a statement: ``We received
the motion today from the CPSC and we are in the process of
reviewing it.'' The company signed a consent agreement in March
under which the sales would stop but commission investigators said
the darts still were being sold in Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
