<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WildfiresRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0881 08-20 0948</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires Rdp, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0881,0969</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fire Burns On Southeast Of Helena</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Elsewhere, a ...,' to CORRECT number of
injured in crash to three sted four. Picks up 6th grav pvs, `The
Warm ...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAITH CONROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters struggled Friday to encircle a
27,000-acre forest fire that had destroyed 10 houses, forced
evacuations and killed cattle in rugged terrain before wind steered
flames away from other houses.
   The leading edge of the 10-day-old Warm Springs Creek fire moved
out of the Elkhorn Mountains toward the small town of Winston,
about 15 miles southeast of Helena. But that area of flames did not
threaten houses or other building, and no more evacuations were
expected, said Art Howell of the Inter-agency Fire Dispatch Center.
   ``There's no more homes in the way,'' he said Friday. ``But that
depends a lot on the weather and the wind's a big factor.''
   A weather inversion trapped cooler air, smoke and flames in the
lower valleys throughout most of the day and kept the 27,000-acre
fire's growth to only 600 acres, said Anne Jeffery, fire
information officer.
   Elsewhere, a helicopter involved in firefighting efforts in
Wyoming's Bighorn National Forest crashed Friday, killing one
person and injuring three others. Firefighters also battled fires
in California, Idaho and Utah.
   The Warm Springs Creek fire grew by 7,000 acres Thursday night,
despite the efforts of 1,700 heavily equipped firefighters. But on
two fronts, the fire took turns that could help suppress it, said
fire information officer Bob Krepps.
   He said westerly wind at about 20 mph late Thursday ``pushed the
fire back into itself'' on its western border, depriving it of new
fuel and lifting a threat to about 500 residents of the Saddle
Mountain subdivision.
   At the fire's eastern edge Friday, flames moved out of forested
high country and onto grassland. ``That's a real benefit to us
also,'' Krepps said, because of the lighter fuel.
   In addition, its movement took it out of rough, inaccessible
terrain into gentler ground where firefighters could work more
easily, said Jerry Adelblue of the Helena National Forest.
   Barring a return of strong, shifting winds, he said,
firefighters should have ``just another day at the office out
there.''
   Although no new evacuations were expected, Broadwater County
Sheriff Rich Thompson said Winston-area residents were on the
alert. ``Everybody's aware of what's going on,'' he said. ``If it
comes down that mountain, they'll have to get out.''
   At least three Air National Guard transport planes, modified to
drop fire retardant, were brought in from Wyoming and California on
Friday and were expected to begin flights Saturday, said Krepps.
   Erratic wind late Wednesday and and early Thursday had caused
the fire to quadruple in size, destroying 10 homes and cabins
scattered in the mountains. One cabin owner lost 30 head of cattle.
   About 40 people remained out of their homes Friday while fire
crews backed by bulldozers shored up lines along the north, east
and west sides of the fire.
   Adelblue said the fire was about 30 percent contained.
   About 35 miles north of Helena, fire crews were expected to
finish mop-up work on a 110-acre grass fire that initially
threatened summer homes near Wolf Creek.
   In southeastern Montana, about 1,000 firefighters began
disbanding Friday after tightening a noose around three fires that
had burned 13,600 acres of scattered timber and grass near Lame
Deer.
   In north-central Montana, 980 firefighters attacked the
4,500-acre Lost Canyon fire on the Rocky Boys Indian Reservation.
It was about half contained by fire lines, said fire information
officer Chris Comstock.
   Comstock said the fire moved farther into thick timber and was
not threatening any buildings. ``I think we're past that point,''
he said.
   About 60 smaller lightning-caused fires burned Friday in the
Flathead River drainage of northwestern Montana.
   Elsewhere, officials had few details about the helicopter crash
in the Cloud Peak Wilderness Area, southwest of Sheridan, Wyo., in
the Bighorn National Forest, said Larry Thoney, a member of the
forest's recreation lands staff.
   Forest spokesman Harvalou Buchanan said the helicopter was
privately owned. The affiliations of the people inside were unknown
and their names were being withheld.
   Wind had pushed the Lost fire in the Bighorn forest past fire
lines and it had charred 5,400 acres, approaching within a mile of
a ranch and summer homes on its northern edge. A wind shift later,
however, helped firefighters, pushing the fire to the west, away
from the area.
   Wind gusting to 30 and 35 mph hampered firefighters in
Yellowstone National Park, and park officials closed a road from
Grant Village to Lewis Lake again Friday because trees that had
been left unburned earlier by the Shoshone fire ignited, sending
flames into the road.
   Elsewhere in Yellowstone, wind pushed the North Fork fire to
cover about 74,000 acres, a growth of 5,000 acres from reports
Thursday. The Norris Junction and Madison Junction campgrounds were
closed while firefighters worked to protect buildings in Norris
Junction from the fire 3 to 4 miles south.
   In southern California, an arson brush fire in the San Jacinto
Mountains grew to 1,073 acres Friday, a fire spokesman said. The
fire, between Barker and Cabazon peaks and on part of the Morongo
Indian Reservation, was expected to be controlled during the night,
said Tim Spann of the state Department of Forestry and Fire.
   Firefighters in southwest Utah contained an 580-acre brush fire,
believed to be man-caused, that burned about 20 miles northwest of
St. George. Firefighters also controlled a 600-acre blaze in
northern Utah.
   Firefighters in Idaho's Challis National Forest squelched a
nearly 14,000-acre fire and were being sent elsewhere.
</TEXT>
