<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Vincennes     08-20 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Vincennes,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran's Envoy Rejects U.S. Claim That Iran At Fault In Airliner
Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Vincennes Report, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian official rejected U.S. claims
that his country was partly responsible for the U.S. Navy's downing
of an Iranian jetliner, and he said the Navy's presence in the
Persian Gulf was to blame.
   ``Our civil airliner was using an internationally recognized air
corridor, used five times a week by the same captain,'' Iranian
Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said Friday.
   During a naval skirmish with Iranian gunboats, the crew of the
USS Vincennes misinterpreted radar and electronic signals from the
civilian airliner and shot it down July 3, killing all 290 people
aboard.
   Conclusions of a U.S. Defense Department investigation released
Friday blamed human error by the crew, but Defense Secretary Frank
C. Carlucci said Iran bore a heavy responsibility for letting the
plane fly over a battle.
   The report said several of the crew's assumptions about the
approaching flight were wrong, including that it was descending
toward the Vincennes and was flying off course.
   Of the crew's mistaken beliefs, which the Defense Department
released immediately after the disaster, Mahallati said:
   ``In the view of the American administration, when such
incidents take place at the price of the lives of 290 people, first
you cannot provide the American people with facts; it is better to
forge information, to misinform them than to keep quiet and wait
until the facts come out.''
   The Iranian envoy laid the blame on the U.S. Navy's presence in
the gulf.
   ``One should conclude that the mere presence of such highly
dangerous equipment, which cannot be controlled even by trained
American personnel, is the source of tension,'' he said. ``By
itself it can cause miseries, one ofter the other.''
   He called for the U.S. fleet to pull out of the gulf, saying the
cease-fire between Iran and Iraq that started today makes it
unnecessary.
   Mahallati also called on the United States to pay reparations to
Iran for the loss of the plane and its passengers and crew and to
issue a formal apology.
   President Reagan sent America's regrets and the United States
accepted responsibility for shooting down the plane. But the United
States blames Iran for sending the flight over a combat zone and
has not apologized.
   Reagan has approved the payment of damages directly to the
families of the victims, but not reparations to Iran, or any
payment that Tehran's government would receive.
</TEXT>
