<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Angola-UNITA     08-20 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-UNITA,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim 42 Government Troops Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas fighting Angola's Marxist
government claimed they killed 42 Angolan government troops this
week.
   UNITA, which sta Total Independence of
Angola, said Friday in a statement released in the Portuguese
capital that its forces killed eight Angolan soldiers in central
Bie province Aug. 14.
   The statement said its fighters killed 19 Angolan soldiers in
southern Huila province Aug. 16, and another 15 in northern Kuanza
North province the same day.
   There was no independent confirmation of the report by UNITA,
which is backed by the United States and South Africa. The reported
fighting occurred despite a cease-fire declared by Angola, Cuba and
South Africa. UNITA is not a party to the talks that led to the
truce.
   On Aug. 12, UNITA said it had killed 42 Angolan soldiers during
the week beginning Aug. 8, when the cease-fire went into effect in
the southern African nation.
   Cuba maintains an estimated 50,000 troops in Angola in support
of President Jose Eduardo dos Santos. Both South Africa and the
United States have justified their support of UNITA on the Cuban
presence.
   UNITA was not involved in U.S.-mediated southern African peace
talks, which are aimed at ending 13 years of civil war in Angola
and securing independence for South African-controlled South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia.
   The sixth round of talks is scheduled to open Wednesday in
Brazzaville, Congo.
   The Angolan government has said it will not negotiate with
UNITA, which seeks to share power in the African nation following
its failure to gain control of the government upon independence
from Portugal in 1975.
   But chief U.S. mediator Chester Crocker has said a final
agreement for the region cannot be reached without an internal
political settlement in Angola.
</TEXT>
