<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BudgetDeficit     08-20 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget Deficit,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Red Ink Surged to $22.9 Billion Last Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal budget deficit climbed by $22.9
billion last month after posting a rare surplus in June, the
Treasury Department said.
   The new batch of red ink brought the deficit for the first 10
months of the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 to $142.0 billion, only
slightly less than the amount for the same period last year.
   Government ledger books were in the black with a $9.3 billion
surplus for June, mainly as a result of quarterly tax payments by
businesses and individuals.
   But the Reagan administration is projecting the deficit for the
fiscal year that ends Sept. 30 at $152.3 billion. That is above the
administration's $146.7 billion deficit estimate in February but
below the $157 billion forecast by the Congressional Budget Office
at the beginning of the year.
   The CBO revised its figures Friday, however, to project a $155
billion deficit. James L. Blum, acting director of the
congressional agency, said stronger economic growth than expected
for the first half was responsible.
   The CBO is not expecting across-the-board spending cuts to be
triggered this month by a law calling for a balanced budget by
1993, Blum said.
   He said CBO projections indicate there is no way the budget
could be balanced by 1993 in the absence of further policy changes,
such as spending cuts or tax increases. The agency, in fact,
projects a $121 billion deficit in 1993 if present policies are
unchanged.
   Surprising economic growth, which has boosted government
revenues and lowered government spending for such programs as
unemployment benefits, has been credited with reducing the deficit
this year.
   Many economists believe the deficit will rise again in the
fiscal year beginning. Oct. 1. The administration, however,
predicts it will drop to $140.1 billion in 1989, when figured
according to guidelines contained in the Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction law.
   Last month's deficit was 2.7 percent higher than the imbalance
in July a year ago.
   Government spending in July actually dropped 6.9 percent when
compared to June. Spending fell to $83.6 billion but tax receipts
dropped even more sharply, falling by 38.8 percent to $60.7 billion.
   Tax receipts for the first 10 months of the fiscal year were up
5.7 percent to $741.7 billion while spending is up 4.6 percent to
$883.7 billion.
   As usual, the largest spending categories were the military,
Social Security and other programs in the Department of Health and
Human Services, and interest on the national debt.
   Military spending totaled $23.9 billion in July and $237.1
billion in the first 10 months of this fiscal year, up 3.3 percent
from the same period last year.
   Social Security payments totaled $17.2 billion in July and $178
billion so far this budget year, an increase of 5.8 percent.
Spending for other HHS programs amounted to $12.0 billion last
month and $130.8 billion this budget year, up 3.3 percent.
   Interest payments on the $2.6 trillion national debt cost $14.5
billion in July and $183.6 billion so far this year.
</TEXT>
