<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     08-20 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Hopes Soon To Set Space Shuttle Launch Date</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third positive development for
the space shuttle program in 10 days _ sealing a fuel line leak _
could lead NASA to announce a launch date soon for Discovery on the
first post-Challenger flight.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has been
aiming for a late September or early October liftoff and hopes to
be able to establish the date by late next week for the
often-delayed mission.
   Technicians bolted a clamshell-like device over the leak in a
Discovery fuel line Friday and filled it with a sealing compound.
   A subsequent pressure test showed no additional leakage, but
officials said they planned to monitor it for a few days. The leak
of nitrogen tetroxide was detected July 14.
   Officials originally thought they would have to move Discovery
off the launch pad and back to a hangar for repair, a move that
could have delayed the flight by as much as two months. But
engineers decided to cut holes in the rear wall of the shuttle's
cargo bay to gain access to the leak.
   The holes were cut Wednesday, and the technicians finished the
job Friday.
   The work was delayed until after the launch pad test firing of
Discovery's three liquid fuel main engines. That critical test,
which certified the engines for flight, was conducted successfully
Aug. 10.
   Another milestone was passed Thursday, when an intentionally
flawed solid fuel booster rocket was test-fired for two minutes at
the Morton Thiokol plant in Utah.
   Officials said that while initial test results looked excellent,
it would be several days before all the data were analyzed.
   The test-firing was the fifth and final prelaunch test for the
redesigned booster, two of which are already attached to Discovery
on the launch pad.
   A faulty joint in one of Challenger's two boosters triggered the
explosion that destroyed the shuttle and killed its seven-member
crew on Jan. 28, 1986.
   Meanwhile, engineers here continued to try to learn why a small
amount of hydrogen leaked during the main engine test. It was
detected in an area where electrical and fuel lines join the
shuttle with its external fuel tank.
   The leak disappeared quickly and was not considered a flight
safety hazard, but officials said they would like to understand why
it happened. They expect to have test results next week.
</TEXT>
