<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CVN--NewOrleansReax Bjt   08-20 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--New Orleans Reax, Bjt,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Should Benefit From GOP Convention For 20 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana, looking to burnish its image,
should reap benefits for many years from the exposure its prize
city received while hosting the Republican National Convention,
some of New Orleans' major boosters say.
   ``New Orleans has never looked better; Louisiana has never
looked brighter,'' said Jim Bob Moffett, head of the Fortune 500
company Freeport-McMoRan and a key convention fund-raiser.
   The city rolled out its plushest red carpet for the GOP
visitors, with sumptuous parties, tasty native cuisine, riverboat
rides and Gov. Buddy Roemer reminding everyone Louisiana was
polishing a tarnished image.
   ``Sooner or later, the message was going to come across that New
Orleans is not strictly a party town or a place for good food and
music,'' said David Jones, president of the New Orleans Chamber of
Commerce. ``We are starting to do the right things to make this a
viable economic center.''
   ``It will probably have gains for Louisiana for the next 20
years,'' said Mervin Trail, a New Orleans businessman and another
key fund-raiser.
   Complaints were few during the four-day convention that ended
Thursday.
   But then, New Orleans handles Mardi Gras every year with 20
times as many visitors and a different kind of crowd, police said.
   ``At Mardi Gras ... it's a party crowd and there are a few more
untoward incidents,'' said New Orleans police Capt. John Hughes.
``It was very good as far as we're concerned.''
   Suffocating humidity and 90-degree temperatures also made it too
hot to misbehave, Hughes said.
   The subtropical weather and the sound system at the giant
Louisiana Superdome drew most of the complaints.
   Technicians began adjusting the system after Sen. Barry
Goldwater, the GOP's 1964 presidential nominee, said he couldn't
hear a word of President Reagan's farewell speech Monday.
   The complaints diminished during the week, but they didn't go
away.
   ``It is not the Superdome system,'' said dome manager Bob
Johnson, explaining that the Republicans installed their own.
   Some of the more conservative delegates were not charmed by New
Orleans' tolerance for the weird, the drunken and the sexy.
   ``Now that we have visited Sodom, where is Gomorrah?'' one
Washington state delegate was reported asking.
   But others were seduced by the city's history, its laid-back
attitudes and the mighty Mississippi River.
   ``Our goal was to put together one of the most successful
conventions in history,'' said Jones.
   Lt. Gov. Paul Hardy said he was hard pressed to find anyone who
wasn't enamored of the French Quarter, the streetcars and the
oak-lined avenues.
   ``I don't believe that we could have spent $1 billion in
advertising and reaped the benefits equal to the fantastic free
press, the free media, we are receiving,'' Hardy said.
``Fortunately, we've been given the opportunity to redeem ourselves
after the world's fair fiasco.''
   The 1984 World Exposition here was a delight for those who
attended but a financial disaster because so many people stayed
away.
   The state's image also has suffered because of the slump in
Louisiana's energy-based economy and its history of shady politics.
   Louisiana's jobless rate has been No. 1 or No. 2 in the country
the last three years. The state's storied corruption spans from the
legendary Huey P. Long _ whose life was chronicled in fictionalized
form in the Pulitzer Prize-winning novel ``All the King's Men'' _
to Roemer's predecessor, Edwin Edwards, who spent much of his third
term successfully defending himself against federal racketeering
charges.
   Hardy said the city already is looking forward to hosting the
Republicans, the Democrats or both four years from now.
   ``It's very seldom both parties have their convention in the
same city,'' he noted.
   It happened in 1952 in Chicago and 1972 in Miami, and Hardy
hopes New Orleans will claim that fame at the next 20-year
interval, 1992.
   ``We're hoping history repeats itself,'' he said.
</TEXT>
