<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoyHero 1stLd-Writethru a0860 08-20 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boy Hero, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0860,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>9-Year-Old Boy Revives Infant Brother</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS dateline.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA NIGUEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old boy rescued his baby
brother from the bathtub and performed mouth-to-mouth resuscitation
after he found the infant had stopped breathing, police said.
   When the 9-month-old child began to breathe again Friday, John
Swain called emergency number 911, then telephoned his mother at
work, said Capt. Don Hayden of the Orange County Fire Department.
   With all that done, the boy waited outside to guide paramedics
to the right house in this community about 50 miles southeast of
downtown Los Angeles, Hayden said.
   ``I've never seen such a calm, cool, young man,'' Hayden said.
``He did it all and he did an excellent job of it.
   ``I have kids of my own and I kinda doubt they could do what
John did. Most adults can't do what he did.''
   The boys' babysitter could not speak English and apparently
didn't realize what had to be done in the situation, Hayden said.
   ``We were thrilled to see someone that young so knowledgeable,''
Hayden said. ``He was real instrumental in saving his brother's
life.''
   It was not immediately known where John learned to give
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, Hayden said. A message left on the
family's answering machine Friday evening was not immediately
returned.
   The infant, Bill, was taken to Mission Community Hospital in
nearby Mission Viejo, where he was treated and released, said
nursing supervisor Sue Donofrio.
   Hayden said another boy, age 3 or 4, also was present but was
``just in awe of everything.''
   The fire captain said he would recommend a bravery certificate
for the 9-year-old hero.
</TEXT>
