<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Politics     08-20 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Politics,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mulroney Government Hit By Kickback Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two legislators from Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney's Conservative government say kickbacks are a way of life
in the administration _ charges that could hurt Mulroney in
elections expected next month.
   The allegations, which surfaced Thursday and Friday, are
political fodder for opposition parties. Polls show the opposition
Liberal Party with a narrow overall lead, followed by the
Conservatives and the socialist New Democratic Party.
   The government said the accusations, by a disgruntled former
Cabinet member and another Conservative member of Parliament, were
unsubstantiated.
   Suzanne Blais-Grenier, a Conservative member of Parliament for
Montreal Rosemount, was quoted in the Montreal daily La Presse as
saying that companies routinely pay kickbacks to get federal
contracts in Quebec.
   Another Conservative member from Montreal, Vincent Della Noce,
was quoted in the Ottawa Citizen as saying the most difficult part
of his job was to ``stay clean.''
   Ms. Blais-Grenier, who resigned as junior transport minister in
1985 in a dispute over aid to Montreal oil refineries, said she
lacked the detailed proof for police charges. But she called for an
impartial commission to investigate federal contracts.
   Ms. Blais-Grenier is under pressure from party leaders in Quebec
not to seek re-election. Other Conservative legislators from the
province met Friday to consider expelling her from the caucus.
   Della Noce was quoted as saying, ``I could put a dozen people in
prison.'' But on Friday, Della Noce said he had no proof and said
he had not expressed himself clearly in the original interview.
   Mulroney was absent from the House of Commons in Ottawa when
opposition leaders hammered the government about the alleged
patronage.
   He is expected to call an election next month, a year before his
five-year term expires, because of Liberal plans to hold up
ratification of the Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement, which is to
take effect on Jan. 1.
   Liberal Raymond Garneau, a leading Quebec legislator, said:
``I've never seen such serious admissions on the part of a
government.''
   But Solicitor General James Kelleher said: ``We as a government
have no information whatsoever to substantiate the allegations.''
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police interviewed Ms. Blais-Grenier
on Friday, and Sgt. George Watts said she ``had no details of any
activity which could permit the RCMP to initiate a criminal
investigation.''
   He said the Mounties had not yet spoken with Della Noce.
   Police confirmed they have asked the FBI to interview officials
at Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. headquarters in New York in
connection with a 2-year-old investigation of possible kickbacks in
a $820,000 Canadian government contract to lease office space from
the company.
   Liberal leader John Turner, poised to take over as prime
minister if his party wins the election, told the Commons that a
royal commission should ``investigate the whole course of conduct
of this government.''
   But Deputy Prime Minister Don Mazankowski dismissed the
suggestion and said the government had moved quickly in the past by
ousting ministers and ordering inquiries when there was ``clear
evidence of wrongdoing.''
</TEXT>
