<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FBI-Hispanics     08-20 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Hispanics,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plaintiff: Discrimination Exists Systemwide In FBI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lead plaintiff in a class-action suit
against the FBI says bias is so institutionally ingrained at the
agency that even he treated fellow Hispanics unfairly.
   ``Bigotry is not the problem,'' Bernardo ``Matt'' Perez
testified Friday in U.S. District Court. ``What we're talking about
is a system of discrimination. As a supervisor, I've been part of
that system. I'm not talking about a particular person. I'm talking
about an organization.''
   Perez and the 310 Hispanic agents who joined him in the lawsuit
contend the FBI discriminates against Hispanics in hiring,
promotion, assignments and discipline. They are seeking damages and
changes in FBI policy.
   About 400 of the FBI's 9,000 agents are Hispanic.
   FBI Personnel Director David Rarity Jr. testified earlier that
the agency does not discriminate against Hispanics.
   Perez, who filed the suit in January 1987, was one of the last
witnesses to testify for the plaintiffs in what is scheduled to be
a two-week, non-jury trial. The plaintiffs rested Friday after five
days of testimony and about 40 witnesses; the FBI is scheduled to
start calling witnesses for its defense Monday.
   During the first week of the trial, agents testified that
Hispanics are assigned a disproportionate number of
Spanish-language wiretaps and temporary out-of-town assignments.
   Because those assignments are not considered as prestigious or
difficult as street investigations, Hispanics are given lower
performance appraisals than non-Hispanics, agents testified.
   Other agents testified that Hispanics are more likely to be
given dangerous undercover assignments, but that they don't receive
the same recognition for that work as non-Hispanics.
   Hispanics are assumed to know Spanish even when they don't, and
non-Hispanic Spanish-speakers are much less likely than Hispanics
to be assigned low-glamor or highly dangerous jobs, according to
testimony.
   Perez said he had no choice but to engage in such discriminatory
actions because the FBI is structured that way and because the
agency has not tried hard enough to hire bilingual agents or teach
agents Spanish.
   Every Hispanic agent who testified expressed fear of retaliation
for cooperating with the lawsuit.
   During three hours of testimony Friday, Perez described what he
called a systematic pattern of discrimination against him.
   Perez, second-in-command at the El Paso bureau, said he first
noticed discrimination when he was attending the FBI academy at
Quantico, Va.
   ``One time the assistant director called me into his office and
said, `What would you say if I called you a blankety-blank blank
blank Mexican?' I said, `I would say you're an ignorant person.'
   ``He said he wanted to know because they would be handing me a
weapon and he didn't want me flying off the handle and hurting
people.''
   Perez testified his problems intensified in 1982, after he was
demoted from the top post in San Juan and sent to Los Angeles,
where he was the No. 2 man under agent Richard Bretzing.
   Bretzing kept Perez uninformed about investigations and
repeatedly harassed him, Perez said. Bretzing demoted Perez twice,
before finally forcing him to El Paso.
   ``Butte and El Paso are considered dumping grounds for agents
who are malcontents,'' Perez testified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
