<HEAD>Soviets Report Pakistan's Suspicions of Sabotage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Tass news agency reported today that
Pakistani authorities suspect sabotage in the plane crash that
killed President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, but it did not mention that
Zia's son suspects Kremlin involvement.
   Zia and 29 others were killed Wednesday when the C-130 military
transport plane they were in exploded and crashed. The blast also
killed U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel, several Pakistani generals
and other senior military men.
   ``It is supposed that this action was perfectly planned and
faultlessly executed, the newspaper Muslim points out,'' said
Tass's Islamabad correspondent in a dispatch. ``An explosive device
might have been installed in the plane.''
   But Tass was silent on comments made Friday in London by Zia's
eldest son concerning possible Soviet involvement. Ijaz ul-Haq
said, ``Some of the superpowers may be involved in it. Naturally, I
would think about the Soviets at this time.''
   Zia was a strong supporter of guerrillas fighting the
Soviet-backed government of Afghanistan, giving them bases in
Pakistan to conduct military operations in Afghanistan. Soviet
officials had accused him repeatedly of violating Geneva accords
that provided for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Tass also reported on some of the theories about the crash. The
dispatch said some officials believe the plane might have been hit
by a missile fired from the ground.
   ``But all officials believe the air crash was not accidental,''
Tass said.
   Tass also noted a Soviet delegation arrived in Islamabad for the
funeral of the 64-year-old leader. The delegation was led by
Vitautas Astrauskas, vice president of the presidium of the Supreme
Soviet.
