<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WildfireRdp Bjt   08-20 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfire Rdp, Bjt,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Battling Montana Wildfires Brace For High Winds</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BIL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAITH CONROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters braced for 40 mph winds today
as they battled an 11-day-old, 27,000-acre wildfire south of Helena
that consumed at least 10 homes and 30 head of cattle.
   Meanwhile, dozens of other fires _ some of them potentially
serious _ broke out in Montana, state and federal officials said.
   In Wyoming, firefighters at Yellowstone National Park also were
expected to encounter high winds, and a team began investigating a
helicopter crash that killed one person in Bighorn National Forest
during firefighting efforts. Wildfires continued to rage in
California, Utah and Idaho.
   The devastating fire near Helena cooled somewhat Friday after
dramatic runs earlier in the week. The fire turned just before
reaching a mountain subdivision with scores of residences and
surrounding ranches.
   ``We're looking pretty good,'' said Anne Jeffery, a fire
information officer.
   She said the fire had grown by 600 acres Friday, but that was a
small increase compared with the 7,000- and 15,000-acre runs the
two previous nights.
   With a part of the fire heading southeast toward flatter land,
officials said they would have more of a chance of checking its
advance once it left the rugged mountain ridges. Another portion of
the fire was moving into even rougher country to the south, but
there was no danger of damage to structures there.
   ``There's no more homes in the way,'' said Art Howell of the
Inter-agency Fire Dispatch Center. ``But that depends a lot on the
weather, and the wind is a big factor.''
   The National Weather Service forecast winds gusting to 40 mph
today.
   Fires were burning over thousands of acres elsewhere in Montana,
many of the blazes resulting from lightning strikes earlier in the
week.
   At least one summer residence was destroyed and others
threatened in a small but dangerous blaze that erupted in logging
slash Friday afternoon about 12 miles northwest of Butte, said Jack
Cullen of the Deerlodge National Forest.
   Other fires were reported in southeastern Montana, including one
that threatened to overrun a ranch in southern Bighorn County near
the Wyoming line.
   Some of the 1,000 firefighters on three fires that have burned
14,000 acres of scattered timber and grasslands near Lame Deer in
southeastern Montana were released from lines Friday, and officials
said those blazes should be controlled by Sunday evening.
   In north-central Montana, 980 firefighters put finishing touches
on a 4,500-acre fire on the Rocky Boys Indian Reservation.
Spokesman Chris Comstrock said the fire should be fully encircled
by tonight if the weather cooperates.
   About 40 smaller lightning-caused fires burned Friday in the
Flathead River drainage of northwestern Montana.
   In Wyoming, Yellowstone spokeswoman Amy Vanderbilt said
firefighters began removing debris and flammable materials from the
structures in the Norris Junction area to prepare for the arrival
of a 74,000-acre fire.
   ``If the forecast brings winds as anticipated, we expect (the
fire) will reach Norris (today),'' she said. The blaze is one of
several burning in the nation's oldest national park.
   In Bighorn National Forest, investigators representing the
agencies fighting a 5,400-acre blaze on Friday reached the site of
the fatal helicopter crash, which left its three other occupants
injured.
   The privately owned helicopter, under contract with the U.S.
Forest Service, crashed in a rugged wilderness area west of the
fire's western boundary.
   A wildfire set by an arsonist in the San Jacinto Mountains of
California charred 1,237 acres but firefighters encircled it, while
a blaze burning out of control blackened at least 300 acres in the
San Bernardino National Forest.
   The arson fire, on part of the Morongo Indian Reservation about
95 miles east of downtown Los Angeles, was contained Friday night
and full control was expected by early today, the California
Department of Forestry said.
   Firefighters contained a 580-acre southern Utah brush fire and
hoped to bring the blaze under control by the weekend, but crews
were being sent to another fire burning in the Wahwah Mountains
about 50 miles northwest of Cedar City.
   Firefighters in Idaho's Challis National Forest squelched a
nearly 14,000-acre fire and were being sent elsewhere.
</TEXT>
