<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0866 08-20 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0866,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle's Hometown Crowd Angered by Questions About His Military
Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTs two new grafs after 7th graf to update with
Washington Post report Quayle passed physical; pkup 8th graf pvs:
``The senator xxx; trims last 2 grafs pvs for space</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What began as a hometown salute to Sen.
Dan Quayle and the Republican ticket turned into mass catcalls and
jeers as thousands of Quayle supporters reacted angrily to
reporters' questions about whether he had strings pulled to avoid
the draft during the Vietnam War.
   As the audience chanted ``Quayle! Quayle!'' the 41-year-old
senator said there was nothing improper in the way he entered the
National Guard in 1969.
   The Republican vice presidential nominee acknowledged that a
family friend made calls on his behalf after he expressed interest
in joining the Guard but insisted: ``I got in fairly.''
   Quayle said he resented implied slurs on his patriotism by media
reports of the controversy and said it should help, not hurt, him
with the voters.
   ``You're going to be surprised at how outraged people and
families that identify with the National Guard around America are
going to be towards these accusations,'' Quayle said as the crowd
cheered.
   Bush campaign officials denied that the event had been
orchestrated to include the crowd in Quayle's first detailed
answers to questions about his military record.
   But the event provided another example of how Vice President
George Bush's running mate has seemed to overshadow the campaign.
   Meanwhile, The Washington Post reported in Saturday editions
that Quayle passed an armed forces physical examination on April 9,
1969, which meant that he would have been eligible to be drafted at
any time after his May 25 graduation day.
   He was called to take the physical by his local draft board
while he was still a DePauw University senior, the Post said. He
entered the National Guard on May 19, but the newspaper quoted
Guard officials as saying they were still reviewing Quayle's
military records, presumably showing when he applied to join, and
could not release them.
   The senator had promised to respond Friday to questions that
have dogged him since he was picked by Bush as his running mate.
   But the opportunity provided by Bush aides came at the end of a
rousing rally for the popular senator at a courthouse square across
from his father's newspaper.
   After Quayle shook hands with his supporters, aides brought him
before a throng of reporters at an outdoor news conference, which
was piped over an public address system.
   Boos and hoots of ``b-o-r-i-n-g'' sang out across the courtyard
as Quayle was asked about the sequence of events that led to his
entry into the Guard.
   Quayle said that during his senior year in college, as he
pondered future military service, he turned to his parents for
advice ``like any 22 year old.'' He faced the loss of his college
deferment after graduation.
   The family discussed the matter with Wendell C. Phillippi, a
former commander of the Indiana National Guard who worked for
Quayle's grandfather at the Indianapolis News, Quayle said, in an
account that was similar to that Phillippi has provided to
reporters.
   ``I did not ask him to make any calls. I told him I was
interested in getting into the Indiana National Guard. ... I would
assume that calls would be made,'' Quayle said.
   Phillippi, who has said he contacted the Guard on Quayle's
behalf, ``knew that I wanted to get into the National Guard and I
hoped he would help me,'' Quayle said.
   ``I did not join to avoid service in Vietnam because by joining
the Indiana National Guard, I could have gone to Vietnam if my unit
had been called up,'' Quayle said.
   The senator said he would not have done things differently if he
had known he would be running for vice president. He said he did
not consider the matter an embarrassment for the ticket and had not
offered to remove himself from the race.
   ``Vice President George Bush agrees with me that it is patriotic
to serve in the Indiana National Guard and he's proud of my
service,'' Quayle said.
   At the rally, Bush praised Quayle as ``a young man of vision, of
character.''
   But it was Quayle for whom the crowd reserved its greatest
enthusiasm. Scores of residents dotted the road to Huntington from
the Fort Wayne airport, and Huntington's police chief estimated the
crowd at the rally to be as many as 20,000 people.
   Quayle told them: ``We have the values, the character, the work
ethic of all small towns.''
   ``My roots, my values, my friends, my neighborhoods _ it is
indeed a proud day, but most importantly, I am just proud of
Huntington,'' he said.
   The crowd roared when he added: ``We love the National Guard.''
</TEXT>
