<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PalauAssassination     08-20 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palau Assassination,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Salii Fatally Wounded By Unknown Gunman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOROR, Palau (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lazarus Salii was fatally wounded
today by a gunman who entered his home. It was the second
presidential assassination in this western Pacific island chain in
three years.
   Salii, in his mid 50's, was shot once in the head in the living
room of his home in the capital city of Koror, said police Officer
Theodore Obak.
   Salii was alone in the house at the time of the 1 p.m. shooting,
while a security guard and a maid were outside, Obak said.
   The president was pronouced dead an hour later at McDonald
Memorial Hospital, he said.
   A .38-caliber handgun believed to be the murder weapon was found
at the house, Obak said.
   Salii had not received any death threats recently, the officer
said.
   Vice President Thomas Remengesau Sr. assumed control of the
nation, Obak said.
   Salii was elected in August 1985 to succeed President Haruo
Remeliik, who was shot to death at his home June 30, 1985.
   Three men were charged with Remeliik's murder, but were
acquitted at trial.
   Palau, with a population of about 15,000, is located 4,593 miles
from Hawaii.
   Palau is the last political entity of the Trust Territory of the
Pacific Islands, which the United States has administered under a
United Nations mandate since the late 1940s. It has been trying to
gain independence from the trust territory.
</TEXT>
