<HEAD>Four Drown In Flooding In Northwestern Bangladesh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods in northwestern Bangladesh have
killed four people and left at least 50,000 people homeless,
officials said today.
   The four drowned Friday when their boat capsized while sailing
to a relief center for the homeless in Chapainawabganj district,
about 75 miles from Dhaka, the capital, said the officials,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The homeless in Chapainawabganj and neighboring Rajbari district
are being housed in relief centers and school buildings or staying
on highways, the officials said.
   The official Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha news agency said the
Padma River was about 22 inches above flood stage. The northwestern
region has been drenched since annual monsoon rains began in July.
