<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfShipping     08-20 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Shipping,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Merchant Vessels Sail Gulf for First Time in Eight Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi merchant vessels sailed the Persian
Gulf and the Gulf of Oman for the first time in eight years today
under protection of a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Iraqi Oil Minister Issam Abdel-Rahim said the Ain Zalah, a
government-owned 35,338-ton oil tanker, took on cargo and left Iraq
to sail the Persian Gulf ``a few hours after the truce began'' at 7
a.m. (11 p.m. EDT).
   Iran and Iraq often attacked shipping during the war, leaving
hundreds of vessels damaged or destroyed in the gulf.
   Iraqi shipping through the gulf stopped shortly after the
outbreak of the war in September 1980. It relied on pipelines for
the export of its oil and on shipments via Kuwait and Jordan for
its commercial trade.
   In his statement, carried by the official Iraqi News Agency and
monitored in Nicosia, the oil minister did not say where the vessel
was loaded or from where it sailed.
   ``Some people were betting that Iraq would not be able to renew
its oil exports through the gulf for months or years after the halt
of the war,'' he said. ``But here we are, and within a few hours,
already launching our first shuttle.''
   He did not disclose the destination of Ain Zalah nor mention
another ship, the Khawla, which shipping executives said sailed
earlier today from a United Arab Emirates port in the Gulf of Oman
toward the gulf.
   The Khawla honked its horns as it began its northbound voyage
from the port of Fujairah toward the Iraqi port of Basra almost
immediately after the truce began, shipping executives said.
   One of the shipping executives monitoring spillovers of the war
on gulf shipping said: ``There has been nothing special, everything
is quiet. ... let's see if it lasts.''
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit says 546
commercial vessels have been damaged in the so-called ``tanker
war.''
   Iraq attacked Iranian-chartered ships and Iran retaliated by
attacking neutral shipping since Iraq's port of Basra was shut down
during the war.
   Lloyd's authoritative register of vessels lists the Khawla as a
3,985-ton cargo vessel that could also be used as a tank-landing
troop ship.'' The Idrissi is not listed.
   The Khawla, which the executives said has an Iraqi captain and a
21-man crew on board, would first sail through a 100-mile stretch
from the Gulf of Oman to Hormuz.
   The vessel would then sail up the gulf to the southern Iraqi
port of Basra, 600 miles from Hormuz.
   Iran's navy chief, Rear Adm. Mohammad Malekzadegan, said Iran
will continue to search vessels in the gulf until ``the
establishment of comprehensive peace'' between the two countries.
   Iranian and Iraqi delegations are scheduled to begin
negotiations in Geneva next week.
   Iran has intercepted hundreds of commercial vessels in the past
years, searching for Iraq-bound war-related cargo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
