<DOCNO> AP880820-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0514EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0882 08-20 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0882,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N.-Monitored Cease-Fire Takes Effect</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Official media...' and inserts 3 grafs after
17th, ```Our bitter...'' to update with Iraqi vessels sailing gulf.
Pick up 18th pvs, ``Direct peace...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cease-fire between Iran and Iraq took
hold this morning after hundreds of United Nations observers moved
into position along the war front to monitor the first truce in
eight years of war.
   Peace officially began at 7 a.m. (11 p.m. EDT).
   Official media in the two countries carried no reports of any
violations or other incidents along their common 730-mile border.
For the first time in eight, years Iraq resumed shipping in the
Persian Gulf.
   Iraqis marched in the streets of Baghdad and in towns throughout
their country late Friday, celebrating what Iraq's media called
that nation's ``victory'' in the conflict.
   In Tehran, acting Commander-in-Chief Hashemi Rafsanjani warned
that Iraq might not want peace and that if it renewed hostilities,
it would face a much stronger Iran.
   Iraq said it was reopening the international airport in the
war-battered southern city of Basra and announced that merchant
ships will soon sail into the Persian Gulf for the first time since
the early months of the Iran-Iraq war.
   As night fell Friday, tens of thousands of people took to the
streets and public parks of Baghdad, many waving portraits of
President Saddam Hussein and chanting slogans in praise of peace.
   ``It is the happiest day in my life,'' said Alaa, an 18-year-old
on Karada Street, a main artery in downtown Baghdad. He said he was
due to be conscripted to the front in January.
   About 150 unarmed Blue Berets from the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military
Observer Group were deployed along the Iraqi side of the border to
monitor the truce, worked out during talks between U.N. Secretary
of State Javier Perez de Cuellar and Iranian and Iraqi leaders.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Cyprus, said 200 U.N. observers would
monitor the truce from the Iranian side.
   The officers were drawn from 24 countries. The United Nations
has set a $75.6 million budget for the mission.
   Rafsanjani, who also is Iran's Parliament speaker and a powerful
protege of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, said in a Friday prayer
sermon:
   ``We are facing two paths, war and peace. We chose peace, but we
are not sure about Iraq. If the enemy wants to continue the war, it
will continue much more seriously.''
   Rafsanjani also noted that ``Iranian forces have become much
stronger and more experienced. This war was a great help to the
export of our revolution and all the world realized that Iran
resisted without any help.''
   The Iraqi general command, in a statement carried by Iraqi radio
and television, also said Baghdad's forces would abide by the
cease-fire ``conscientiously and responsibly.''
   It expressed hope for better relations with Iran but added:
   ``Our bitter experience, and the sea of blood that the Iranian
aggression caused, make it our responsibility not to deal with Iran
on the basis of wishful thinking but on the basis of reality so
that we are not cheated again.''
   Iraq's oil minister, Issam Abdel-Rahim said Ain Zalah, a
government-owned 35,338-ton oil tanker, loaded up and sailed down
the Persian Gulf ``a few hours after the truce began.''
   Another Iraqi ship, the Khawla, left the United Arab Emirates
port of Fujairah in the Gulf of Oman and headed north for the Iraqi
port of Basra in the Persian Gulf almost immediately after the
truce began, said shipping executives speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Iran and Iraq often attacked shipping during the war, leaving
hundreds of vessels damaged or destroyed in the gulf.
   Direct peace talks between the foreign ministers of Iran and
Iraq open Thursday in Geneva, mediated by Perez de Cuellar.
   The Geneva talks will focus on the peace plan decribed in
Security Council Resolution 598.
   The resolution calls for the cease-fire, withdrawal of troops to
their own territory, exchange of prisoners of war, direct peace
talks, and establishment of an impartial commmission to establish
responsibility for the outbreak of the conflict.
   The resolution was passed in July 1987 and accepted by Iraq at
that time. Iran finally accepted in last month, clearing the way
for the U.N. talks that led to the truce.
   Most Western estimates of the number of people killed since the
conflict broke out in September 1980 range from a half million to 1
million, with some figures even higher.
   The countries participating in the U.N. peacekeeping force are
Argentina, Australia, Austria, Bangladesh, Canada, Denmark,
Finland, Ghana, Hungary, Indonesia, India, Ireland, Italy, Kenya,
Malaysia, New Zealand, Nigeria, Norway, Poland, Senegal, Sweden,
Turkey, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
