<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan 3rdLd-Writethru   08-20 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0428,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands March In Zia Funeral Procession</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 8 grafs with cortege at mosque, details and color.
Pickup 7th graf pvs ``Secretary of...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of mourners
gathered at the huge Faisal Mosque today in a funeral procession
for President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq. Some clutched portraits of Zia
and shouted, ``We will mourn you forever!''
   The funeral cortege made its way slowly to the mosque as the
crowds, composed mostly of men, chanted from the Koran, holy book
of the Islamic faith, and shouted praises of their leader who died
in a plane crash Wednesday.
   The lawns and terraces surrounding the mosque were jammed and
scores of men clambered up on the roof and clung precariously to
the soaring dome.
   The flag-covered, flower-draped coffin was transferred from a
military ambulance to a gun carriage pulled by soldiers about 500
yards from the mosque.
   ``My heart is crying for him, and I am praying for his
salvation,'' said 74-year-old Mian Ihtishamuddin, who came by bus
from Peshawar, 100 miles away.
   Soldiers with bayonets and riot police with bamboo sticks lined
the streets leading to the modern mosque, the world's largest. The
crowd was generally orderly.
   The funeral procession was broadcast live by state-run
television. The cameras focused briefly on the tear-stained faces
of Zia's widow, Shafiq, and a son, Ijaz.
   Investigators were still searching for the cause of the crash
that killed Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel, and 28 other people.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz landed Friday night with
Robert Oakley, designated to replace Raphel.
   ``This journey is a journey in sorrow,'' Shultz said. ``I will
be expressing the heartfelt sorrow of President Reagan and the
American people for Pakistan's tragic loss.''
   The United States was one of Zia's staunchest backers.
   Thousands of people poured into Faisal Mosque for prayers
Friday, the Islamic holy day, and heard eulogies for their late
leader. A sermon extolled Zia as the ``shaheed,'' or martyr, of the
Moslems.
   ``It's difficult to imagine Pakistan without Zia,'' said a
bearded army captain watching the crowd.
   Across the border in India, the government of Jammu and Kashmir,
an Indian state also claimed by Pakistan, passed a resolution
expressing its ``profound grief and anguish'' over the death of Zia.
   The state government also lifted a curfew in Srinagar, the
summer capital, for three hours. Security officials said the city
of 700,000 was calm. Four people were killed in the state Thursday
in riots stemming from Zia's death.
   In the absence of any government statement on Wednesday's
in-flight explosion, Pakistani newspapers were rife with
speculation.
   Their unattributed and undocumented theories ranged from
deliberate sabotage by unspecified enemies to a bomb hidden in a
basket of mangoes.
   A Pakistani government information officer discounted all the
press accounts. ``Nothing is known yet,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``The investigators are still at the
scene.''
   Zia's eldest son, Ijaz ul-Haq, said he believed the plane was
sabotaged, and he told Britain's Independent Television News that
``naturally'' he suspected the Soviets.
   The Soviet Union's official Tass news agency today reported on
the Pakistani media reports of sabotage, but it did not mention
Ijaz ul-Haq's comments.
   Like the United States, Pakistan supports rebels fighting the
Soviet-backed government in neighboring Afghanistan. The Soviet
Union had often accused Pakistan of violating a U.N.-mediated
agreement providing for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan.
   Acting President Ghulam Ishaq Khan has said he would not rule
out sabotage in Zia's death but would await a report from the
military investigators.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said a team of Americans was assisting in the investigation at the
crash site near Bahawalpur, 330 miles south of Islamabad.
   Two Urdu-language newspapers said police had detained people for
questioning about the crash, but a senior official police who spoke
on condition of anonymity said the detentions were unrelated to the
crash.
   The mass circulation Jang newspaper said those detained were
employees of Bahawalpur airport. Markaz, a smaller newspaper, said
16 people were detained near Bahawalpur but did not say whether
they worked at the airport.
   Nawa-i-waqt, an authoritative Urdu daily, said investigators had
recovered the plane's flight recorder.
   Ishaq Khan, 73, who succeeded Zia,64, by virtue of his post as
Senate chairman, said he would carry out Zia's pledge to conduct
nationwide parliamentary elections Nov. 16. But like Zia, he has
not said whether the presidency also will be at stake in the voting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
