<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Republicans 1stLd-Writethru a0528 08-20 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Republicans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Lauds Bush For Straight Advice; Gives No Examples</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Adds 2 grafs Demo response; fixes typos thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan lauded Vice
President George Bush on Saturday as a strong leader who has given
him ``straight-from-the shoulder advice'' and offered voters a
clear ``road map'' of his intentions if elected president.
   ``I'm proud to stand with him,'' Reagan said in his weekly radio
address, delivered from his vacation hideaway in the Santa Ynez
mountains 20 miles north of Santa Barbara.
   The president will travel to Los Angeles on Tuesday for a series
of political speeches, including a joint appearance Wednesday with
Bush.
   Reagan, who watched Bush's acceptance speech at the Republican
National Convention on television in his ranch house, said, ``After
hearing his speech Thursday night, all Americans could see what
I've seen for eight years _ dedication, integrity, and commitment
to principle, a strong man and a strong leader.''
   ``And one other thing,'' the president said. ``George has always
given me straight-from-the-shoulder advice and counsel, on how we
could advance our vision for the future. And he's always been
candid with me when we disagreed.''
   He gave no examples.
   The president drew a contrast between the detailed platform
written by the Republicans in New Orleans and the relatively brief
platform adopted at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta
last month.
   ``That document is a plethora of platitudes and it points up the
difference between the two parties,'' he said. ``Our friends in
Atlanta won't tell you what they will do if they get elected, but
George Bush and Dan Quayle already have.
   ``George and Dan and our party have spread their road map out on
the table for all to see, while the other guys won't tell us where
they're going and won't even give us directions,'' the president
said. ``It will take more than platitudes to convince the American
people.''
   Reagan also had praise for Quayle, the Indiana senator Bush
chose for his vice presidential running mate. He made no reference
to the controversy over Quayle's service in the Indiana National
Guard during the Vietnam War.
   ``The strength and wisdom of George Bush was reflected this week
in the strength and wisdom of the Republican Party itself _ just as
the energy and enthusiasm of the party were reflected in the energy
and enthusiasm of Senator Dan Quayle,'' he said.
   ``Dan was elected to the Senate on the day I was first elected
president. Dan shares with George Bush and me a vision of an
America and a world no longer threatened by the specter of nuclear
attack. That's why Dan has labored with conviction for the
Strategic Defense Initiative.
   ``And he shares a vision of opportunity for all Americans. And
that's why he's stood with George Bush and me throughout the fight
to lower tax rates and increase opportunity for all Americans.''
   In the Democratic ``response'' to Reagan's remarks, Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, the Democrats' vice presidential nominee, said the
Republicans have stood silent on major economic issues such as
trade.
   ``America is paying a heavy price for that Republican neglect
and indifference,'' Bentsen said in the radio remarks taped Friday
for broadcast Saturday.
</TEXT>
