<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Ships     08-20 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Ships,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baghdad Says Iranian Helicopter, Warship Shadow Iraqi Vessel</HEAD>
<HEAD>with AM-Iran-Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq sent three merchant vessels into the
Persian Gulf on Saturday for the first time in nearly eight years
but said one of them was shadowed by an Iranian helicopter gunship
and a warship.
   Iran said its navy, backed by helicopters, intercepted and
searched the vessel, the Khawla, in the Strait of Hormuz but
allowed it to proceed after finding no weapons aboard.
   Baghdad sought to test its right of navigation in the gulf after
a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect in the region early
Saturday morning.
   Iran said it launched a number of boats into the strategic Shatt
al-Arab waterway to ``display their power and readiness to defend
the borders of our Islamic homeland.''
   Sovereignty over the waterway, which flows between Iran and Iraq
and is Iraq's only outlet to the sea at the Persian Gulf, is a key
point of dispute between Iran and Iraq.
   In another development, Iranian Oil Minister Golamreza Aqazadeh
said the port of Genaveh, north of Kharg Island, with a capacity to
export 2 million barrels of oil a day, renewed operations.
   Aqazadeh said that with the cease-fire taking effect, Iran was
giving top priority to the reconstruction of the oil industry to
generate foreign currency reserves from oil exports.
   Iraqi Oil Minister Issam Abdel-Rahim said the Ain Zalah, a
35,338-ton government-owned tanker, sailed from the northern gulf a
few hours after the truce began at 7 a.m.
   The minister, quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency, did not
say which port the ship sailed from.
   He said the Khawla sailed from the Gulf of Oman coast of the
United Arab Emirates and was later shadowed by an Iranian
helicopter gunship and a ``war vessel'' as it passed through the
Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the gulf. He said Iran made ``an open
attempt to provoke the ship.''
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency quoted navy officers as
saying the ship was intercepted and searched in the Hormuz by
``naval units supported by helicopters.'' It said the ship was
found to be empty and allowed to proceed.
   Iranian naval chief Rear Adm. Mohammad Malekzadegan said earlier
Iran would continue to intercept ships in the Persian Gulf until a
comprehensive settlement was reached in the war.
   The Iraqi captain of the Khawla, speaking in a ship-to-shore
contact with The Associated Press, declined to discuss his cargo
and said ``there are no problems.'' He did not mention Iranian
helicopters or warships.
   A third Iraqi merchant vessel, the Idrissi, sailed into the gulf
from the port of Khor al-Zubair south of Basra on its way to the
Strait of Hormuz, the Iraqi agency reported. No other details on
the ship were given.
   Earlier, Baghdad radio quoted Iraqi naval commander Rear Adm.
Abed Mohammed Abdullah Abdullah as saying that if Iran searched
ships, that would be a ``a serious violation of the cease-fire''
and Iraq would ``strongly resist'' such a measure.
   Tehran radio, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp., said
Iranian forces launched a number of boats flying the Iranian flag
into the Shatt al-Arab as U.N. observers watched. ``Complete calm
exists on both shores of the river,'' it said.
   The radio report did not say what type of boat was launched or
precisely where. The Shatt al-Arab is the only navigable channel
between the Gulf and the city of Basra, Iraq's only major port.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
