<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Plane-Tires     08-20 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane-Tires,1st ld-writethru, a0541,170</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in third graf that Hess is spokesman for airport,
not Eastern</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines Boeing 727 jet blew two
tires Saturday as it landed and skidded to a stop at National
Airport, but none of the 156 people aboard was injured, officials
said.
   The plane, Flight 158 from Miami, came to a halt at the
intersection of the busy airport's two longest runways, forcing
their closure. Hundreds of passengers were stranded as other
flights were delayed, said Eastern spokeswoman Kathleen Starman.
   The runways were closed for 3{ hours after the midmorning
landing before the plane was finally moved, said Dave Hess, an
airport spokesman.
   The tires on the left side of the main landing gear blew out and
the gear partially collapsed when the jetliner landed, Hess said.
The plane tried to veer off the runway but couldn't clear the
intersection, he said.
   The 149 passengers and seven crew members were evacuated through
steps in the back of the plane and taken by bus and van to the
National terminal, said Ms. Starman.
</TEXT>
