<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru   08-20 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0535,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Celebrate but Baghdad Reports Violation of Cease-fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Iraq reporting soldier killed
in cease-fire violation. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BAG1,3,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqis crowded into stores and waved flags
Saturday on the first day of a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war
with Iran, but the government said Iran violated the truce by
killing an Iraqi soldier.
   U.N. observers reported no violations on the front.
   Iraq also said that in the Strait of Hormuz, an Iranian
helicopter gunship and a ``war vessel'' shadowed an Iraqi merchant
ship, one of three sent into the gulf waters to test the truce.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said an Iranian soldier
infiltrated an Iraqi ground position and shot a private. It did not
say whether the Iranian soldier was captured.
   ``Iraq did not retaliate for the Iranian violation,'' the Iraqi
agency said. It was not clear exactly where the incident occurred,
and Iran and the United Nations had no immediate comment.
   Earlier, Maj. Gen. Slavko Jovic, commander of the U.N. Iran-Iraq
Military Observers Group, said the ceease-fire was holding. He said
he had ``no information about violations and everything is going
very fine.''
   Most of the 350-man observer group began patrolling the 730-mile
warfront at 7 a.m. Saturday, capping a year-long effort by the
United Nations to halt a war that has cost an estimated 1.5 million
dead and wounded since it broke out in September 1980.
   Iraq accepted the cease-fire shortly after the Security Council
approved it in July 1987, but Iran accepted it only July 18 after a
series of defeats.
   Jovic's chief assistant, Canadian Col. John Annand, told
reporters that a few technical hitches in transport and
communications were ``the growing pains of a new mission with two
countries who have absolutely no experience with this type of
thing.''
   Cease-fire celebrations continued into the morning. Processions
of drivers honking their horns wound through the streets of this
city of 3.5 million, many waving Iraqi flags.
   Many Iraqis celebrated the cease-fire at shopping centers, where
they have suffered severe shortages of consumer goods over recent
years.
   Minister of Trade Mohammed Mahdi Saleh termed the day ``an
economic festival'' to mark celebrations of the ``great victories
scored by our people.''
   In an interview published by the official army newspaper
Al-Qadissiya, Saleh said President Saddam Hussein ordered the
ministry to flood state-run stores and local markets with goods.
   ``The goods will be unlimited in quantity and that includes all
kinds of goods available at the ministry's stores,'' including such
sought-after items as televisions, radios, freezers and other
electrical appliances, Saleh said.
   Iraqis lined up in front of state department stores by the
hundreds to get first crack at the new goods.
   Iraqi Oil Minister Issam Abdel-Rahim said an Iraqi merchant
vessel, the Khawla, sailed from Fujairah in the Gulf of Oman and
was later shadowed by an Iranian helicopter gunship and a ``war
vessel'' as it passed through the Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the
Persian Gulf.
   The minister, quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency, said
Iran made ``an open attempt to provoke the ship.''
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus,
claimed Iranian naval units backed by helicopters ``intercepted and
searched'' the ship but let it go when no weapons were found.
   Iranian naval chief Rear Adm. Mohammad Malekzadegan said earlier
that Iran would continue to intercept ships in the Persian Gulf
until a comprehensive settlement was reached.
   Baghdad radio quoted Iraqi naval commander Rear Adm. Abed
Mohammed Abdullah as saying Iraq would ``strongly resist such a
measure,'' which he called a serious violation of the cease-fire.
   In a welcome sign of a gradual return to normal life, an Iraqi
jetliner completed the first Basra-to-Baghdad flight since the
early days of the war. Civilian traffic was halted at Basra's
airport when Iranian shelling devastated the southern port city.
   Iraqi soldiers continued to man anti-aircraft batteries atop
many of Baghdad's major high-rise buildings, and the government
warned that ``the road to peace might be littered with hardships.''
   Iraqi and Iranian negotiators are to meet face-to-face Thursday
in Geneva to begin work on a comprehensive settlement of the
conflict.
   An unidentified Iraqi military spokesman was quoted in
Saturday's newspapers as saying:
   ``The cease-fire is likely to lead to comprehensive peace for
which Iraq has been endeavoring. But there could be some who will
try to hamper this process. This requires that Iraq should remain
vigilant and not be complacent.''
</TEXT>
