<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chile-Stange     08-20 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Stange,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chile Police Commander Says He Might Be Willing To Negotiate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Chilean military
junta says he would be willing to negotiate with the civilian
opposition on far-reaching political changes if the government's
candidate is defeated in this fall's plebiscite.
   ``If the `no' wins (in the yes-or-no vote), there would have to
be an accord between those who won the majority and the junta,''
Gen. Rodolfo Stange told the Fort Lauderdale News-Sun-Sentinel in a
story published Saturday. ``And if they want changes in the
constitution, well, there would have to be an agreement on what
those changes would be.''
   It was the first time a member of the four-man junta, which
includes the president, Gen. Augusto Pinochet, seemed to accept the
opposition's argument that the defeat of the junta's nominee should
be interpreted as a vote of no confidence that could lead to
constitutional reform.
   Stange, who is also commander of Chile's national police, made
his comments Friday in his office in Santiago, Chile, to reporters
for the Fort Lauderdale newspaper and The Independent of London.
   Pinochet has been in power since the bloody right-wing coup in
1973 that overthrew elected-Marxist President Salvador Allende.
Pinochet has overall control of the nation's political direction
but shares power with the other three members of the junta.
   Sometime this fall, probably in October, Chileans are slated to
vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on a single candidate for president, to be
chosen by the junta late this month. It is expected that Pinochet
will be that candidate.
   According to the constitution, which was enacted by the junta in
1981, if the junta candidate is defeated, then Pinochet would stay
in power for one year and hold open elections. If Pinochet wins the
plebiscite, he would stay in power until 1997.
   Stange put no limits on what could be negotiated between the
junta and civilian political leaders in case of a ``no'' victory.
Even the armed forces' wide powers in the national security council
could be discussed, he said.
   Previously, military authorities have rejected any suggestion
that a possible defeat in the plebiscite might lead to major
structural changes in the system.
   Stange even questioned whether Pinochet should be the man on the
ballot in the plebiscite. The nominee should be ``someone who has
the will and ability to unite all Chileans so that the transition
to democracy occurs in peace and stability,'' he said.
   Asked if Pinochet is best equipped to fulfill these
requirements, Stange said: ``That is a difficult question. ... My
responsibility is to find a candidate acceptable to the majority.''
   The ideal candidate should be a civilian, Stange said.
</TEXT>
