<DOCNO> AP880820-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 1723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Consumers     08-20 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Consumers,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders Increase In Consumer Goods Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Saturday announced a program to
increase production of consumer goods said continuing shortages
could undermine Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform efforts.
   The Council of Ministers, or Soviet Cabinet, said it has ordered
state-run industries to produce $38 billion more consumer goods in
1989 and 1990 than originally planned, the official Tass news
agency reported.
   Tass also reported the council plans an 18 percent increase in
the total amount of consumer goods originally planned for 1991-1995.
   It did not say what the original plans were.
   The new economic directive also provides for an increase in the
production of refrigerators and other electric appliances, and
promises to eliminate within two years shortages in automobile
spare parts.
   The Council of Ministers directed the Soviet automobile industry
to manufacture 2.3 million cars a year by the mid 1990s, Tass said.
In the first half of 1988, 386,000 cars were produced.
   The newspaper Moskovskaya Pravda reported Saturday that the
black market price for a car is at least $28,000, about triple the
average official price, accompanied by at least a one-year wait for
delivery after the order is placed. Tass said the number of
refrigerators, washing machines and kitchen appliances produced for
every 100 Soviet families is 20 percent less than in Western
countries. The gap is even bigger in cars, video, hi-fi and radio
equipment.
   The new economic plan calls for production of 13.6 million
television sets a year, up from 10 million this year, and 2 million
video recorders compared to 70,000 this year.
   The government said it will buy Western equipment for garment
factories in order to increase by 50 percent the number of coats
and jackets produced, and shirts and knitwear by 20 percent, Tass
reported. It did not say how much Western equipment would be
purchased for the clothing industry, or where it would be bought.
   In the past, the Soviet Union invested heavily in manufacturing
equipment, but many times has not been able to install or operate
it properly.
   Shops selling fashionable clothes are rare in Moscow and the
more attractive goods often are sold out the same day they are
displayed. Long lines form for many other goods that are of poor
quality but are in short supply.
   The ministers said the three years of Gorbachev's reform efforts
have failed to improve the supply of goods to Soviet consumers and
the Kremlin leader himself has repeated the criticism many times.
   The Soviet leader has encouraged decentralization of control
over local industry managers and better pay incentives for good
work to try to improve the supply and quality of consumer goods _ a
major goal of his reforms.
   But Gorbachev and his advisers acknowledge that consumers still
are no better off than they were when the reforms began.
   Tass said a meeting of the policy-making Central Committee at
the end of July ``pointed out that the ongoing scarcity of goods
has an adverse impact on people's attitudes to perestroika (or
restructuring), subverts their trust in the reality of the
transformations planned.''
   But the new government plan says nothing about improving the
chronically poor quality of Soviet goods, which Western economists
say is the crucial problem. They say production actually should be
reduced in many cases to allow production of more modern and
popular items.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
