<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-West Bank, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0553,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Bank Palestinians To Get Temporary, Two-Year Passports</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS last graf to CORRECT that Israel captured Gaza Strip
from Egypt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank are no longer citizens of Jordan, but they may obtain
temporary two-year passports from the kingdom if they need a travel
document, officials said Saturday.
   It was the latest in a series of decisions by King Hussein to
sever links with the West Bank and turn over responsibility to the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``All citizens residing in the West Bank before July 31 are
considered Palestinian citizens, not Jordanians,'' Prime Minister
Zaid Rifai was quoted as saying by the official Jordan News Agency.
   He said West Bank residents can ``obtain temporary Jordanian
passports, valid for two years, if they desire.''
   The old five-year passports issued to West Bank residents before
July 31, the date that King Hussein announced he was cutting links
with the West Bank, will be valid until their expiration date.
   But after then, residents can obtain only the two-year document.
   Another senior Jordanian official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the new law would ``allow West Bank residents to
travel, but not to qualify for Jordanian citizenship.''
   About 850,000 West Bank residents carry a permanent Jordanian
passport, valid for five years and renewable on demand for another
permanent passport.
   In addition, a minority of the 650,000 Gaza Strip residents
already hold temporary Jordanian passports valid for three years.
They will be replaced with the two-year passports upon expiration.
   Hussein has dissolved the lower house of Parliament, half of
whose members were Palestinian; dissolved the occupied territories
ministry; canceled a $1.3 billion development plan for the
territories; and laid off or retired thousands of state employees.
   Rifai said if schools in the West Bank opted for the Jordanian
system, the Ministry of Education in Amman would make arrangements
for exams to be held on the West Bank.
   But he said the ``tests would be corrected and grades would be
given by the ministry in Jordan.''
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip
from Egypt in the 1967 Middle East War.
</TEXT>
