<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Singer-Checker     08-20 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singer-Checker,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supermarket Checker Who Sang At LA Olympics Still at Her Register</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the 1988 Olympics in South Korea approach,
supermarket checker Vicki McClure vividly recalls singing to the
world during the opening ceremonies of the Summer Games four years
ago.
   ``It was the most spectacular moment. It was bigger than life,''
she said. ``It was a really magical experience.''
   Ms. McClure, a musical unknown, sang the hit ``Reach Out And
Touch (Somebody's Hand)'' at the opening ceremonies of the 1984
Olympics at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
   But Ms. McClure, 34, who still works three days a week as a
checker at a market in Los Angeles in addition to taking part-time
singing jobs, is glad in a way that her moment in the spotlight
wasn't a springboard to a famous singing career.
   ``I didn't have any expectations,'' she said in a telephone
interview from her Santa Monica home. ``I'm not disappointed for
what has happened because being thrust in at that level with my
inexperience would have been a mistake.
   ``I really wouldn't have had an inkling of how to handle it,''
she added.
   The $7 million opening ceremony had a cast of thousands and was
staged before a capacity crowd of 90,000 and an international
television audience.
   The show included a 1,000-voice choir, a 750-piece marching
band, a 100-piece symphony orchestra, 7,500 athletes and 2,500
pigeons.
   Ms. McClure appeared as the lead singer for the Los Angeles Jazz
Choir, a position originally intended for a star of the caliber of
Diana Ross or Leontyne Pryce.
   She said she was first hired by the Olympics as a musician who
could serve as a standby soloist. But after Olympics officials
heard her sing, they chose her to perform with the jazz choir
because they liked the idea of having an unknown singer in the
spotlight.
   ``It was kind of in keeping with the amateur spirit of the
Olympics,'' she said.
   Ms. McClure said she is happy working as a part-time
professional singer, performing solo at banquets and ceremonies and
with the group Daddy's Money, which does nostalgic and rhythm and
blues songs.
   ``I haven't really done a Vicki McClure act as of yet,'' she
said. ``I'm still looking for a repertoire. It's hard to find
material you're comfortable with by yourself.''
   She said that as long as she can support herself she is happy
continuing with her current musical path.
   ``It takes a lot of artistic development to find your niche,''
she said.
</TEXT>
