<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Newspaper     08-20 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Newspaper,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Newspaper Seized In Police Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided a printing company to crack down
on a newspaper that published an interview with Peru's best-known
guerrilla leader, the newspaper's editor said Saturday.
   Luis Arce told reporters that 40 police officers swept into the
Lima printing firm Imprenta Pedro Leon before dawn Friday, arrested
owner Pedro Leon and four employees and confiscated 100,000 copies
of El Diario.
   Police sources confirmed the raid took place, but refused to
provide details.
   Arce charged the government with harassing the paper in an
effort to force it out of business.
   ``We have no guns, not even a knife ... The government is trying
to put us out of business,'' he said.
   The government alleges El Diario is the voice of the Shining
Path guerrilla organization, whose insurgency to impose Marxist
rule in Peru has claimed more than 15,000 lives in eight years. El
Diario is openly Marxist but has denied links to the guerrilla
movement.
   But independent observers say El Diario reflects the ideology
and political objectives of the rebel group more accurately than
any other publication.
   The Lima tabloid drew widespread criticism on July 24 when it
published a 48-page interview it claimed was the first with Shining
Path leader Abimael Guzman since the rebels launched their
insurgency in 1980.
   Four days later, President Alan Garcia asked Congress to pass a
law empowering the government to close media believed to support
terrorists. Lawmakers are studying the proposal.
   El Diario reprinted the interview July 31, the day on which the
newspaper's contract with its printer expired. The agreement was
not renewed, according to Arce.
   Since then, El Diario has had trouble finding another printer
and has appeared only intermittently, Arce said, adding that the
government has intimidated Lima printing companies into not working
with the newspaper.
   Arce said the edition seized by police was a special third
printing of the Guzman interview.
   In the article, Guzman was quoted as saying the Shining Path
would not hold talks with the government until the rebels were
ready to change from a guerrilla to a conventional war.
   He was quoted as saying Peru's chronic economic problems
eventually would foment a general insurrection led by the Shining
Path, but did not give a timetable for the revolt.
</TEXT>
