<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Mandela     08-20 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Mandela,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandela Rebounds From Tuberculosis, Doctors Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nelson Mandela's health has
improved and the jailed black leader has an excellent chance of
completely recovering from tuberculosis, doctors said Saturday.
   Leading newspapers, meanwhile, predicted the leader of the
outlawed African National Congress soon may be released from
prison. The Star, the country's largest daily, said Mandela is
``one step from freedom.''
   The 70-year-old Mandela, South Africa's best-known black leader,
was diagnosed with tuberculosis and transferred Aug. 12 from
Pollsmoor Prison to nearby Tygerberg Hospital in Cape Town.
   ``Mr. Mandela is responding well to our treatment,'' said Dr.
J.G.L. Strauss, superintendent of Tygerberg. ``He is cheerful and
is up and about.''
   Strauss said the prognosis for Mandela's full recovery was
``excellent.''
   Mandela's family asked the government Friday to release
Mandela's medical records to resolve ``nagging doubts'' about how
he contracted tuberculosis.
   The family questioned whether conditions at Pollsmoor Prison
caused Mandela's illness and whether prison doctors could have made
a quicker diagnosis.
   Mandela first complained about his health July 28 but was not
transferred to Tygerberg Hospital until two weeks later, the
government's Prisons Service has said.
   The government insists Mandela has been receiving the best
possible treatment. Strauss said doctors who have seen Mandela
include the Swiss president of the European Society of Pneumology,
Dr. Heinrich Hertzog.
   Meanwhile, The Star quoted Minister of Information Stoffel van
der Merwe on Saturday as saying security concerns were the main
reason Mandela remained imprisoned.
   ``There is no reason to punish him further for the crimes of the
1960s,'' van der Merwe told The Star. ``The government is now
concerned with ... what the (security) implications would be for
the country if he were released.''
   Mandela has been imprisoned since 1962. He is serving a life
sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-led
government.
   Botha said Thursday that Mandela's release was under serious
consideration. He indicated the government was trying to persuade
Mandela to accept its condition that he renounce violence.
   The president has been making the same offer since 1986.
However, Mandela has said the government's 1960 decision to ban the
African National Congress, which operated peacefully at the time,
left him no option but to fight.
   Mandela says he will disavow violence only if the government
lifts its ban on his group, dismantles the apartheid system of
racial segregation and extends full political rights to the
nation's 26-million member black majority.
   The African National Congress, based in Lusaka, Zambia, is the
main black group attempting to undermine the government and
apartheid.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5
million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts,
schools and health services.
   The pro-government newspaper Beeld reported Saturday that
influential academics with close government contacts were urging
authorities to ``bring the Mandela issue to an end.''
   Kurt von Schirnding, the country's former U.N. ambassador and
head of the South Africa Foundation, a private research group, told
Beeld the government should try to avoid the appearance of ``bowing
to international pressure.''
   But he added, ``the issue must be resolved.''
   State-of-emergency regulations in effect since 1986 restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of
detainees, some forms of protest, and a broad range of statements
the government considers subversive. Enforcement of the regulations
has not been comprehensive.
  
</TEXT>
