<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 1828EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Earthquakes     08-20 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Earthquakes,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquakes Jolt Lima; No Damage Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two powerful earthquakes jolted the capital
Saturday and gave its 6 million residents a scare, officials said.
   Civil Defense officials said Saturday they had no reports of
injury or damage, but said they received dozens of phone calls from
worried residents.
   The first quake, measuring 4.7 on the Richter scale, struck
shortly after midnight Friday, said Victor Orbegozo, an earthquake
specialist for the Geophysical Institute of Peru. He said it was
centered 15 miles south of Lima.
   Another temblor briefly rocked the city late Saturday morning.
Orbegozo said it measured 4.5 with an epicenter 18 miles southeast
of Lima.
   He said two other quakes of lesser strength struck Saturday
afternoon, but seismic data had not been tabulated.
   Scientists believe that a fracture in the earth's crust 35 miles
below the Pacific coastline south of Lima had caused the quakes,
Orbegozo said.
   An earthquake registering 4.5 on the Richter scale, which
measures ground motion on a seismograph, can cause moderate to
considerable damage.
