<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Afghan     08-20 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Afghan,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Expect Pakistani Aid To Continue Despite Zia's
Death.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebel leaders said Saturday
they expect continued economic and military aid from Pakistan
despite the death of President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Zia, the U.S. ambassador to Pakistan and 28 other people
perished in the crash Wednesday of a C-130 military plane.
   Anti-communist rebels have been fighting Afghanistan's
Soviet-backed government for 10 years. About 3 million Afghan
refugees have fled into northern Pakistan and that is where most of
the rebel organizations have their bases.
   Zia, a staunch Moslem, was a strong supporter of the Afghan
insurgents.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, a rebel leader who had close ties with Zia,
said that after the president's death ``I personally met with
senior people (in the Pakistani government) who assured me the
policy will not change.''
   Ahmad Gailani, chairman of the seven-party rebel alliance, said
he did not expect any major change.
   ``We never put all our hopes in one person, in one country,'' he
said. ``Our support is from God almighty and he will support us in
the future.''
   But some Pakistani opposition leaders have said Zia's policies
prolonged the Afghan war and prevented the refugees from returning
home.
   The Pakistan Peoples' Party, a significant contender in the Nov.
16 general election, wants a program to quickly return the refugees
to their homeland. It says they have strained Pakistan's economy
and there is resentment in northern Pakistan by local residents who
say they have lost their jobs and businesses because of the
refugees.
   Zabihullah Mojaddiddi, vice president of an ``interim''
government organized by the rebels, said, ``We don't see any chance
of the Pakistan Peoples' Party winning an election. We hope not.''
   A car bomb exploded Saturday in Kabul, the Afghan capital,
wounding six people, according to Tass, the official Soviet news
agency.
   In a dispatch filed in Moscow, Tass quoted the Afghan news
agency Bakhtar as reporting the bomb exploded at about 11 a.m. on
one of Kabul's main streets. Kabul has been the target of an
increasing number of bombings and rocket attacks since Soviet
troops began withdrawing from Afghanistan under an agreement signed
in Geneva on April 14 between Afghanistan and Pakistan. The Afghan
rebels did not participate in the negotiations or accept the accord.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979
to help the Marxist government and had an estimated 100,000
military personnel in the country when the withdrawal began. The
withdrawal is to be completed by Feb. 15, and on Sunday the Soviets
said they had met their commitment to withdraw half the force by
Aug. 15.
   They also accused Pakistan of violating the accords by
continuing to aid the rebels but said the Soviet troops would be
withdrawn as scheduled.
</TEXT>
