<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats 1stld-writethru a0524 08-20 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats, 1st ld-writethru, a0524,770</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: inserts 2 grafs after 9th graf pvs. to UPDATE; pickup 10th
graf pvs. ``Both were'' etc.
^By JOHN KING</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STONEWALL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said Saturday that
George Bush is taking the Republican Party ``farther and farther
away from the mainstream'' and questioned the Republican vice
president's vow to create 30 million jobs if elected president.
   The Democratic presidential candidate linked up with his vice
presidential running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, for a visit with
Lady Bird Johnson at the LBJ Ranch.
   After having breakfast with Mrs. Johnson, Dukakis paid tribute
to her and saluted late husband for ``the passion and comitment he
had to people, especially to people who needed a helping hand and a
leg up on the road to opportunity.''
   Then they all visited Lyndon B. Johnson's grave, moving quietly
beneath giant oak trees.
   Dukakis never referred to President John F. Kennedy by name but
recalled that ``another son of Massachusetts'' won the presidency
in 1960 with Johnson as his running mate.
   It was an obvious effort to keep alive the Boston-Austin
connection that Democrats hope will help them at the polls.
   At a news conference at the 250-acre ranch, Dukakis said Bush's
choice of conservative Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana as his running
mate signaled an effort to bring GOP policies further to the right.
   ``My sense is that the Republican Party is moving farther and
farther away from the mainstream while Senator Bentsen and I are
campaigning on Main Street,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic ticket mates also appeared together at a rally in
nearby Johnson City before splitting up. Dukakis headed to a county
fair in Lebanon, Tenn., on his way home to Boston while Bentsen
traveled to a fund-raising dinner in Florida.
   At the Wilson County Fair in Lebanon, Dukakis inspected
prize-winning cattle, fed milk to a calf and rode on a mule-pulled
cart.
   Bentsen will fly to Boston on Monday to attend a national
security briefing at Dukakis' home, to be conducted by CIA Director
William Webster.
   Both were on the road during the Republican National Convention;
Dukakis campaigned in several states while Bentsen stayed close to
home in Texas except for one quick trip to Arkansas.
   On Saturday they continued to pound away at the two issues they
have accused Bush of ducking: the federal trade and budget deficits.
   And Dukakis was skeptical of Bush's declaration that he could
create 30 million new jobs if elected.
   ``Harold Wilson once said never put a date and a number in the
same sentence,'' Dukakis said. `I think it's good advice. ... I
don't see any evidence that this Republican ticket even understands
how to create jobs, especially in those parts of the country that
are hurting and hurting badly.''
   He declined to predict how many new jobs he could help create as
president.
   Dukakis predicted the Democratic ticket would carry Texas,
considered a Bush stronghold until Dukakis tapped Bentsen to run
with him.
   Bentsen, in a message to his fellow Texans, praised Dukakis'
integrity and record of economic development.
   ``This man from New England really talks our language,'' Bentsen
said. ``And that language is one that is understood across the
country.''
   Dukakis and Bentsen continued to criticize Quayle by mentioning
Bentsen's leadership role in the passage of several major bills,
including a trade bill President Reagan is scheduled to sign this
week.
   ``On that trade bill this administration was no help
whatsoever,'' Bentsen said. ``I'll bet they'll try very hard to do
that,'' the senator said when asked if he thought Republicans would
try to take credit for the bill.
   There was a somewhat awkward moment at the ranch when Dukakis,
with Mrs. Johnson standing behind him, discussed his opposition to
the Vietnam War. President Johnson escalated the U.S. presence in
Vietnam.
   ``It was a war that divided this country, that in some ways
we're still recovering from,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis and Bentsen, accompanied by their wives and Mrs.
Johnson, were greeted by Mrs. Johnson when they arrived at an
airstrip on the ranch. She served them a country breakfast of
bacon, eggs, grits, biscuits, peaches and figs.
   ``I have great confidence and great pride and high hopes for
these four folks,'' Mrs. Johnson told reporters gathered outside
her home on the bank of the Pedernales River. Hereford cattle, a
favorite of the late president, roamed across a road as Dukakis'
motorcade drove off.
</TEXT>
