<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtHay     08-20 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Hay,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowans Prepare For Idaho Hay Harvest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa cattle farmers in desperate need of
hay to supplement drought-depleted supplies would love to accept
Idaho's offer of help, but few farmers can take the time off to go
and get it.
   The Iowa Farm Bureau is having trouble finding volunteers to
travel to Idaho and harvest hay because many farmers can't leave
home for a week to 10 days. The drought of '88 has forced them to
haul water and feed to cattle that normally would be grazing and
drinking on their own, said Don Murdock, a regional manager for the
bureau.
   A group of cattle farmers in parched southern Iowa is to leave
Monday for a 37-hour bus ride to Orofino, Idaho. But Murdock said
Saturday that while transportation, housing and meals all have been
donated, he still has only 20 farmers who can go. He would like to
get at least 40.
   Murdock said the Idaho Farm Bureau offered unlimited hay to
drought-stricken farmers if they would supply the labor for the
harvest.
   The venture is a cooperative effort of the farm bureaus in Idaho
and Iowa, with Greyhound donating a bus for the trip, the
Burlington Northern railroad donating freight space for the hay and
three banks putting up cash for meals along the way.
   Murdock said that while he is having difficulty finding farm
workers with the time to spare for the harvest, farmers were
extremely grateful for the offer.
   ``I have never worked on a project that has received the
acclamation, pleasure and impact this has,'' he said. ``People
become emotional when they learn this has been donated.''
</TEXT>
