<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Scene 1stLd-Writethru   08-20 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Scene, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0540,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Dockworkers Dig In For Long Standoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Poland's new...' with seven grafs new
material to add color, quotes from Jastrzebie mine strike; picks up
10th pvs: The mood...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GERARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SZCZECIN, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the main gate of Szczecin's
sprawling, strikebound port, a steady stream of women pushing baby
carriages and carrying buckets of food has replaced the normal
caravan of rumbling trucks.
   The wives of the longshoremen who went on strike Wednesday are
visiting about 2,000 men holed up on the docks of this Baltic city
on the Odra River near the East German border.
   ``We've got enough food stockpiled to last us a week,'' said a
beaming worker in his late 20s.
   Supporters of Solidarity, to which the men belong, carried bread
and vegetables through gates festooned with the flags and banners
of the outlawed independent union federation.
   Shortly after the strike began, negotiations broke down between
management and workers, who remain steadfast in their demand that
the government grant legal status to their union.
   In 1981, the communist government arrested many Solidarity
leaders in a military crackdown. Solidarity was outlawed in 1982.
   Solidarity leaders said the harbor strike and a walkout by the
city's transit workers arose from growing dissatisfaction with the
policies of state-run unions and anger over Poland's deteriorating
economy.
   The strikes have idled port operations and brought city transit
services almost to a standstill.
   At the July Manifesto mine in Jastrzebie in the southwest,
spirits also were high. Strikers sitting on makeshift wooden
benches spoke bravely.
   ``We won't go back to work until we get a second trade union,''
shouted one miner tanned by the hot summer sun. ``We will stay here
until the end,'' said another. Still others cheered.
   ``We believe the government will have to recognize us because we
are in the heart of Poland's industry,'' said miner Jan Golec.
   Management for the first time Saturday allowed three priests
into the mine, and a Mass was planned Sunday. The strikers erected
a 6-foot white cross with a picture of Pope John Paul II in front
of the building where the strike committee meets.
   Mine officials also permitted workers to buy cigarettes, food
and bottled drinks at a lunchstand inside the mine.
   Meanwhile, some miners expressed bitterness about their economic
plight. ``A miner is forced to work Saturday and Sunday to be able
to support his family,'' said Jerzy Nowosielski, of the mine's
strike committee.
   Poland's new wave of labor unrest began Tuesday, when coal
miners at the July Manifesto mine declared their occupation strike.
   The mood quickly spread to Szczecin, a city of 395,000 and the
country's largest port city after Gdansk.
   ``The strike began spontaneously, when we got our paychecks last
week,'' said Edward Radziewicz, a forklift operator who heads the
Interfactory Strike Committee representing dock and transit
workers. ``It became very clear that we had no one to stand up for
our interest and that we were on our own.''
   Workers here said they had no faith in the official union's
ability or desire to represent them and complained that rampant
inflation has cutting into their buying power.
   ``The union represents management and its interest and not us,''
said a young dockworker who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A 50-year-old crane operator said he could barely make ends meet
on his salary.
   ``After 30 years on the dock I get paid $67 a month. A
black-and-white television costs $156 dollars. We got an 11 percent
pay increase recently, but prices went up by more than 40
percent,'' he said.
   Transit workers at a nearby bus depot had similar views.
   ``Reinstatement of Solidarity is the first step in setting up
further talks,'' said Romuald Ziolkowski, head of the depot's
strike committee. ``We can negotiate wages later.''
   He said 1,800 transit workers were on strike and were posted at
the depot's gates, which were blocked by buses.
   Thousands of residents in outlying apartment complexes Saturday
trudged past empty bus stops into town to shop. State-run food
stores said sugar and flour were quickly disappearing from store
shelves.
   The run on staples indicated that residents were bracing for the
possibility of more strikes and shortages.
   City officials urged factory and tourist buses in service to aid
stranded commuters. But the transit strike has been a boon for the
city's taxi drivers.
   ``Business is flourishing,'' said one driver in downtown
Szczecin.
</TEXT>
