<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Blast Hits Crowded Cafe In Haifa; 25 Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police saying blast caused by hand
grenade; updates extent of injuries, number of Arabs detained, adds
new quotes and description; CORRECTS names of two youngsters
injured, reversing their first names; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL HIRSCHHORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hand grenade exploded Saturday night near
a crowded sidewalk cafe and toy store in downtown Haifa, wounding
at least 25 people, including seven members of one family, police
and witnesses said.
   Fifteen Arabs were detained for questioning after the explosion
at 9:15 p.m. in the center of this northern port city, police
reported.
   Hospital officials said Dan Meir, 8, lost parts of both legs and
suffered head injuries and his 2-year-old brother Yonathan was
wounded in the stomach.
   The boys' parents, their 6-year-old sister Keren, and
grandparents who were visiting from France suffered minor injuries.
   Keren told people at the Rothschild Hospital the boys were
pointing at toys they wanted their grandparents to buy when there
was an explosion, witnesses said. At the hospital she jumped from
the stretcher to hug her grandfather as he was being carried into
the emergency room.
   A police source said the blast was caused by a hand grenade that
was either thrown or rolled along the sidewalk.
   ``Suddenly there was an explosion. Small children flew into the
air,'' said David Taub, 32, an art student who was standing near
the cafe.
   ``People were in shock. We tried to cover their wounds. We took
off pieces of our own clothing and ripped table cloths to tie their
wounds,'' he told The Associated Press.
   Doctors at the Rothschild and Rambam hospitals said four of the
victims suffered severe or moderate injuries and the others were
slightly wounded.
   The police source, speaking with the condition he not be
identified, said three Arabs were seized as they ran from the scene
and 12 other Arabs also were detained for questioning.
   The grenade blew up between the toy store Land of Wonders and
the crowded Cafe Kapulski in a pedestrian mall.
   There were pools of blood, pieces of bloody clothing and a pair
of a child's sandals along the sidewalk.
   Scores of anxious relatives crowded the waiting room at the
Rothschild Hospital.
   Bracha Ornan, 48, said she was waiting for her son's fiancee to
be treated. ``There was glass everywhere,'' she said. ``I grabbed
her (the fiancee) and ran.'' Mrs. Ornan suffered slight cuts from
flying glass.
   The attack increased tension in Haifa, a city where 223,000 Jews
and 20,000 Arabs live.
</TEXT>
