<DOCNO> AP880820-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   08-20 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0580,0872</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftists Protest Administrative Detentions; 25 Hurt By Bomb In
Haifa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with police reporting Haifa
blast caused by grenade, reports of Arab death; moves up and
updates number of Arabs killed during uprising; DELETES 14th graf
pvs, `At least...' with outdated material</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli leftists demonstrated Saturday near a
desert prison camp to protest the detention of thousands of
Palestinians held without trial for up to six months.
   In Haifa, 25 people were wounded when a hand grenade exploded
near a toy store and sidewalk cafe. Arab doctors said three
Palestinians were wounded in clashes with Israeli troops in the
occupied Gaza Strip and the army reported Israeli soldiers killed
three armed Palestinian guerrillas in southern Lebanon.
   Police and witnesses said the grenade blew up in downtown Haifa
at 9:15 p.m. Among the wounded were seven members of one family.
   Hospital officials said Dan Meir, 8, suffered severe leg and
head injuries and his 2-year-old brother was wounded in the stomach.
   Slightly injured were their sister, 6-year-old Keren, parents,
and grandparents who were visiting from France, they said.
   Police said 15 Arabs were arrested for questioning in the
northern port city.
   Meanwhile, Israel radio said an Arab from the West Bank village
of Tamun died Saturday, two days after he was shot by soldiers who
fired at villagers attacking the troops with knives. It identified
the victim as Saoud Abdallah, 22. The army said it could not
confirm the report.
   At least 249 Palestinians and four Israelis have been killed
since the Arab uprising began in December.
   The violence broke out in the Gaza Strip hours after the army
lifted curfews in seven of the strip's eight refugee camps, ending
five days of restrictions imposed to quell widespread rioting.
   In its report on the action in southern Lebanon, the army said
soldiers shot and killed three heavily armed Arab guerrillas who
were on their way to Israel to carry out an attack. It said the
Israeli troops suffered no casualties.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a pro-Syrian
PLO faction, claimed responsibility. The group said its guerrillas
raided an Israeli border settlement before being killed.
   About 200 Israelis, including three parliament deputies,
demonstrated near the Ketziot detention camp in the Negev Desert,
said organizer Zahava Galon.
   The protesters demanded that the nearly 3,000 Palestinians held
by Israel for up to six months without trial in so-called
administrative detention either be tried or released. About 2,100
administrative detainees are held at Ketziot.
   ``Anyone who is suspect should be brought to court and in front
of a judge,'' Dedi Zucker, a legislator of the left-wing Citizens
Right Movement, told The Associated Press in a telephone interview.
   Ketziot, a camp of open-sided tents, was erected several months
after the Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip broke out last Dec. 8. Thousands of Palestinian
activists have been arrested in the past eight months.
   The Israeli demonstrators also demanded improved prison
conditions and called for a commission of inquiry into a prison
riot last week in which two inmates were killed and one wounded.
   Ketziot inmates have complained they are exposed for many hours
a day to the brutal desert sun and not given enough water.
   The protest, organized by groups opposed to Israel's occupation,
was staged at a gas station about three miles from Ketziot after
security forces barred protesters from approaching the camp.
   Demonstrators released about 100 balloons at the gas station.
``We wanted the detainees to see that people are demonstrating on
their behalf,'' said Ms. Galon.
   About a dozen followers of the right-wing Tehiya Party staged a
counter- demonstration nearby, calling for all of the leftists to
be imprisoned at Ketziot. They also demanded the deportation of all
administrative detainees, Ms. Galon said.
   In Gaza City, Arab youths shouting ``Allahu Akhbar'' (God is
great) blocked main roads with burning tires. They also stoned army
patrols.
   Two 18-year-old Palestinians were shot during clashes in the
Rafah refugee camp near the Egyptian border, hospital officials
said. At Shifa Hospital in Gaza City, a 68-year-old man was treated
for a gunshot wound in the right foot, doctors said.
   An 85-year-old Gaza City woman suffered multiple fractions in
the leg and foot. Shifa doctors quoted the woman as saying she was
beaten by soldiers after trying to stop them from arresting her son.
   The army said the guerrillas seeking to infiltrate Israel were
intercepted just north of the Israeli-Lebanese border fence in the
central section of Israel's self-declared security zone.
   The Israeli unit spotted the guerrillas around midnight Friday
south of the village Maroun a-Ras and opened fire, killing all
three, the army said.
   The last reported infiltration attempt from Lebanon occurred May
10 when Israeli troops shot and killed a Lebanese guerrilla in the
security zone, a six-to-10-mile buffer strip north of the
international border.
   Israel set up the security zone in 1985 after withdrawing the
bulk of its troops from Lebanon, ending a three-year occupation.
</TEXT>
