<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NewsweekPoll     08-20 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newsweek Poll,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Lead for Bush After Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush would defeat Gov.
Michael Dukakis by 51 percent to 42 percent if the presidential
election were held now, according to a Newsweek poll released
Saturday.
   The poll of 1,000 registered voters, conducted by telephone
Thursday and Friday, found Bush riding a favorable reaction to the
Republican convention, which concluded Thursday.
   The poll found that 43 percent of those contacted said they were
more likely to vote for Bush because of what they saw or read
during the convention. Fifty percent said they were more likely to
vote for Bush after watching the vice president's speech on
Thursday.
   The poll, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points, found the registered voters thought Bush would
be better than Dukakis at keeping the country out of war, creating
good economic conditions, dealing with the drug problem and
reducing crime.
   Dukakis was perceived as stronger at helping families and
children, it said.
   Thirty-six percent said Bush's choice of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle
as his running mate made them more likely to vote Republican, while
33 percent said it made them less likely to do so.
   The poll showed that 74 percent said their opinions were not
less favorable toward Quayle because he chose to serve in the
National Guard during the Vietnam War, the poll said.
</TEXT>
