<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FrequentFlier     08-20 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frequent Flier,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frequent Flier Kids Visit Zoo, Tijuana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Georgia youngsters traveling through
Southern California on a trip won by a generous frequent flier
visited San Diego Zoo on Saturday and headed for the Mexican border
town of Tijuana.
   ``The kids are just ecstatic,'' said Clark Howard, a retired
travel agent who traveled 26,338 miles on 68 flights in 48 days to
meet the requirements of an Eastern Airlines promotion for a free
ride West.
   The 30-member group includes 25 children ages 9 to 15 from an
Atlanta boys' and girls' club and the local Big Brothers program
and five chaperones. The group toured Hollywood, hit the beaches
and visited Disneyland.
   ``The zoo is especially interesting for the kids,'' said Howard.
``Yesterday, they got to see the make-believe animals at
Disneyland. Today, they're seeing the real thing.''
   Next stop was a trip across the border to Tijuana.
   ``Many of these kids have never been anywhere and have never
seen any culture other than their own,'' Howard said.
   Howard, 33, who retired after selling a chain of travel agencies
and now hosts a radio travel show in Atlanta, took part in the
Eastern Airline promotion with the children's trip in mind.
   The airline offered 60 free tickets to anyone making at least 60
flights totaling more than 25,000 miles in 60 days as part of its
60th anniversary celebration.
   Howard paid $2,110 out of his own pocket for the 68 flights he
took between May 6 and June 25.
</TEXT>
