<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stld-writethru a0557 08-20 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st ld-writethru, a0557,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: inserts 3 grafs after 2nd graf pvs. to UPDATE with poll;
pickup 3rd graf pvs. ``Bush joined'' etc.
^By JERRY ESTILL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush and the young, Vietnam-era senator he
hopes will share the White House with him pitched horseshoes
Saturday and Bush said the flap over his running mate's National
Guard membership is a ``tempest in a teapot.''
   The Democratic contenders sought political solace at the grave
site of Lyndon B. Johnson.
   Despite the GOP controversy vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle, Bush received some favorable news from a Newsweek poll
released Saturday. It said Bush would defeat Gov. Michael Dukakis
by 51 percent to 42 percent if the presidential election were held
now.
   The poll of 1,000 registered voters found that 43 percent of
those contacted said they were more likely to vote for Bush because
of what they saw or read during last week's Republican convention.
Fifty percent said they were more likely to vote for Bush after
watching the vice president's acceptance speech on Thursday.
   The poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
   Bush joined Quayle during an appearance at the Ohio State
Fairgrounds to answer questions about the Indiana senator joining
the National Guard during the Vietnam War.
   The current vice president said his reasoning in selecting
Quayle as his running mate ``was very sound, and the American
people are going to see that, loud and clear.''
   Bush conceding that questions about Quayle had overshadowed
their campaign plans, but declared, ``I think it will turn out to
be a tempest in a teapot.''
   He said news media attention to the questions reminded him of
``bluefish, when they're swimming around, all in a frenzy.''
   Quayle defended himself for the second straight day at an
impromptu news conference and also said he had not misled Bush
campaign officials in talks leading to his selection.
   ``I told the Bush campaign there was nothing embarrassing in my
military record, and I'm sticking to it,'' he said.
   On a lighter note at the fair, both Bush and Quayle pitched a
few horseshoes along with contestants in the state contest. Bush,
who pitches horseshoes for relaxation at his home in Washington,
scored a ringer after several tries. Quayle did not.
   It was still early in the day when Michael Dukakis signaled his
determination to fight hard to get Texas and other Southern states
in the Democratic column on Election Day.
   Running mate Lloyd Bentsen confided to reporters that the Greek
immigrant's son spooned picante sauce onto his grits _ ``seeming to
like it'' _ during breakfast at the LBJ Ranch.
   Dukakis was stopping off in Nashville, Tenn., en route back home
to Boston for the night. Bentsen was swinging through Florida on
his return home to Washington.
   After breakfast, Dukakis and Bentsen and their wives drove over
to the bank of the Pedernales River where former President Johnson
is buried in a family plot shaded by huge live oak trees.
   ``I have great confidence and great pride and high hopes for
these four folks,'' Johnson's widow, Lady Bird, told reporters.
   Reporters were kept well back while Mrs. Johnson and her guests
strolled near the grave.
   Earlier, Dukakis had saluted the man buried there for ``the
passion and commitment he had to people, especially to people who
needed a helping hand and a leg up on the road to opportunity.''
   There was a somewhat awkward moment when Dukakis, with Mrs.
Johnson standing behind him, reminded reporters of his opposition
to the same Vietnam War that Johnson had escalated.
   ``It was a war that divided this country, that in some ways
we're still recovering from,'' Dukakis said.
   There was a certain irony given the furor surrounding Quayle's
acknowledgement that he sought assistance _ needed or not _ to get
into the Indiana National Guard in 1969 while many other young men
entering combat in Vietnam. The controversy over the war ultimately
forced Johnson to decide against seeking re-election in 1968.
   Quayle has said he is and was then, at age 22, a supporter of
U.S. involvement in the war. He also has said there should have
been more of an all-out effort to win the conflict.
   Although he figuratively passed the GOP political baton to Bush
last week at the party's New Orleans convention, President Reagan
gave it another hearty wave Saturday.
   In his weekly radio address, broadcast from his mountain
hideaway in California, Reagan said Bush as vice president never
held back from straight talk.
   ``George has always given me straight-from-the-shoulder advice
and counsel on how we could advance our vision for the future,''
said Reagan. ``And he's always been candid with me when we
disagreed.''
   Reagan gave no examples.
</TEXT>
