<DATELINE>MARION, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People often ask Vernell Sellars if he's
coming or going.
   Sellars has welded together two front ends of junked Honda
Civics, creating a single car with two engines, two steering
wheels, two sets of headlights _ two of almost everything. Separate
keys crank each end.
   Both cars _ 1980 and 1982 models that had wrecked back ends _
were sawed in half just behind the front doors. Since Civics are
front-wheel driven, building the new creation posed few problems.
   ``You can drive it either way; it's legal,'' said Sellars, 49,
noting the Secretary of State's office inspected the dual vehicle
and granted him license plates. ``You can do figure-eights. You can
do doughnuts. You can do anything you want.''
   Sellars, who owns a salvage business, said he and employee Dan
Watkins started the car this spring and finished it in mid-May for
about $2,500.
   ``It blows people's minds,'' said Sellars of the black,
standard-transmission car with light-blue interior and
air-conditioning. ``People can't believe what they're seeing.
