<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Rally     08-20 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Rally,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chilean Youths Rally in Anti-Government Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of youths packed a city street
Saturday for a rally called to protest the military's selection of
a presidential candidate.
   The protest, which was authorized by the right-wing military
government of President Augusto Pinochet, was peaceful and festive.
Participants danced, waved banners and chanted anti-government
slogans while police remained several blocks away.
   Journalists estimated the crowd, which filled several city
blocks, to number about 25,000.
   From a colorfully painted stage with the snow-capped Andes as a
backdrop, opposition youth leaders urged the crowd to vote ``no''
in the upcoming referendum. ``If he (Pinochet) doesn't leave, we're
going to throw him out,'' declared Yerko Ljubetic, leader of a
group called Youth Movement for a No Vote.
   ``Our triumph must be at the ballot box and also in the streets,
the plazas and the neighborhoods,'' he said.
   The government plans a yes-or-no vote in early October on a
single presidential candidate to be picked by the commanders of the
army, navy, air force and national police. Pinochet, who is army
chief, is expected to be the nominee.
   If the military-picked candidate wins the referendum, the
candidate will begin an eight-year term in March. If a mayority of
voters rejects the candidate, open elections will be held in 1990.
   Pinochet, 72, led a coup in September 1973 that ousted the late
President Salvador Allende, an elected Marxist. His government does
not include opposition representation.
   Another opposition rally, expected to be larger, is planned for
Sept. 4. It has not yet received government authorization, but
organizers said it will be held even if permission is refused.
</TEXT>
