<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drownings 1stLd-Writethru a0577 08-20 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drownings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0577,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman, Boy Drown But `Heroes' Rescue Girl From Flooded Creek</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 3 and 4 with 2 grafs to UPDATE with victims'
identities, search to resume Sunday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BATESVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby sitter and a young boy drowned
when a rain-swollen creek swept their car off a bridge, but two men
who tried to warn the victims managed to pluck a second child from
the water.
   ``They're heroes in my book,'' said Detective Mike Bare of the
Indiana State Police. ``It's fair to say they risked their lives,
both of them.''
   The body of Mary Wilhelm, 41, of Oldenburg was found Saturday
about 4 miles downstream from the site of the accident. Rescuers
would resume searching Sunday for the body of 4-year-old Matthew
Zins, also of Oldenburg, police said.
   Mrs. Wilhelm had been baby sitting with the boy and his
6-year-old sister, Sarah Zins, and was taking them home on a rural
road about 8 p.m. when a rainstorm flooded Salt Creek.
   Two friends, Randy Macyauski and William D. Effing, happened to
be watching the flooded creek and tried to warn the car to stop as
4 feet of water gushed over a primitive bridge, police said.
   After the vehicle plunged into the stream, Macyauski ran
downstream and dove in to rescue the girl, who had climbed out a
window of the car. Effing hung out over the creek on a tree limb
and tried to grab the woman and boy, but the limb broke and Effing
was swept downstream a few hundred feet before he managed to climb
out.
   The bridge consisted only of a concrete slab, Bare said, adding
that most residents of the area know to use caution with such
bridges during sudden storms.
   ``In the flash flood conditions such as existed last night, it's
not at all uncommon for the water to go over the top of the slab,''
he said Saturday. ``We've had several instances in the past where
cars have been washed off.''
   The accident occurred about 6 miles north of Batesville, in
southeastern Indiana.
   ``These slabs (bridges) are characteristically found on roads
that are quite lightly traveled,'' Bare said. ``This area is the
very definition of rural.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
