<DOCNO> AP880820-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 2113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-Carter     08-20 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Carter,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Carter Meets with PLO Officials, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter met in Cairo
with a senior official of the Palestine Liberation Organization, an
Egyptian Foreign Ministry official and a PLO source said Saturday.
   The sources, speaking on condition they not be identified, said
Carter met for two hours Friday night with Hani Hassan, political
adviser to PLO leader Yasser Arafat.
   Carter flew to London Saturday where he was scheduled to spend
the night before leaving Sunday for the United States. He bypassed
reporters at London's Heathrow Airport after he arrived from Cairo
with his wife, Rosalynn.
   The Cairo sources said Carter and Hassan had an ``extensive
review'' of Palestinian issues but they gave no details.
   They said the talks were at a presidential guest house where
Carter stayed and Saeed Kamal, an Arafat aide, also was present.
   Carter arrived in Egypt Thusday for a private visit at the end
of an Africa tour that included Kenya, Uganda and Ethiopia. He met
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the Mediterranean port of
Alexandria Friday and returned to Cairo for the talks with Hassan.
   The United States government prohibits its officials from
dealing directly with the PLO. The restriction has been in effect
since 1975 with successive U.S. administrations, including
Carter's, insisting that the PLO must renounce violence and
recognize Israel's right to exist before direct talks can be held.
   Egypt was unable to arrange a meeting in Cairo last week between
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Richard Murphy and Palestinian
representatives. Of six delegates proposed by the PLO through the
Egyptian government, Murphy approved four but rejected two on
grounds they were too closely connected with the PLO.
   The PLO refused to change its list and the plan collapsed.
</TEXT>
