<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NepalQuake     08-20 0119</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nepal Quake,000</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strongest earthquake in the area in 54
years shook the Himalaya Mountains early Sunday along the
India-Nepal border, the U.S. Geological Survey reported.
   Initial seismograph readings placed the center of the quake
about 100 miles southeast of Katmandu, the capital of Nepal.
   Geological Survey monitors in Golden, Colo. recorded the
earthquake at a preliminary magnitude of 6.7 on the Richter scale.
The quake occurred at 6:09 a.m. Sunday (7:09 p.m. EDT Saturday).
   The Survey said this was the strongest earthquake in that part
of the Himalayas since Jan. 15, 1934, and it was capable of causing
excessive damage had it occurred in an urban area.
   There were no reports on casualties.
</TEXT>
