<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HuntBrothers-Troubles     08-20 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunt Brothers-Troubles,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silver Decision One of Many Adversities Hunts Face</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hunt Brothers-Silver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury's decision that the Hunt brothers must pay
over $130 million in damages to a Peruvian company is the latest in
a series of problems faced by the sons of the late Texas oilman
H.L. Hunt.
   After six months of testimony and five days of deliberations, a
federal jury in New York jury determined Saturday that the brothers
conspired to corner the world silver market in the late 1970s,
thereby ruining the investments of Minpeco S.A., the Peruvian
government's mineral marketing company.
   The ruling comes as the Hunt brothers try to complete settlement
of a two-year, $1.5 billion dispute with 23 lenders. The dispute
has absorbed much of the fortune left the brothers by their father.
   Hunt Energy Corp. Vice President Tom Whitaker said the Hunts
were disappointed by the verdict ``and obviously disagree with it.
   ``However, this is merely a first step in a long civil process
that has been going on for nearly eight years,'' Whitaker said.
``Motions, raising other issues, will be filed to set aside or
modify this verdict.
   ``The brothers are confident that this wrong result will
eventually be overturned as they proceed through the court system.''
   Nelson Bunker Hunt, 62, William Herbert Hunt, 59, and Lamar
Hunt, 56, mortgaged much of their share of the family legacy to
cover $1.1 billion in losses they suffered when the market crashed
in March 1980.
   The loss also prompted their sisters, Caroline Rose Hunt
Schoellkopf and Margaret Hunt Hill and representatives of another
brother, Haroldson ``Hassie'' Hunt Jr., to separate their fortunes
from those of their brothers, significantly cutting into the wealth
of their trusts.
   After the silver losses, the Hunts' International Resources Co.
and Great Western Sugar Co. went bankrupt and are now defunct.
   In the spring of 1986, two Hunt businesses, Placid Oil Co. and
Penrod Drilling Co., failed to make payments on a total of $1.5
billion in loans. In July 1986, after attempts to renegotiate the
loans failed, the three Hunt brothers sued their banks and lenders,
charging them with negotiating in bad faith and trying to take over
their offshore oil businesses.
   Soon after, the Hunts put the most valuable loan collateral _
Placid Oil and William Herbert Hunt's trust _ into Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection to guard against foreclosure. Later, the
trusts of Lamar and Nelson Bunker were put into Chapter 11 for the
same reason.
   In the settlement they proposed to the lenders, the Hunts would
pay $663.5 million from funds raised through Placid operations,
primarily in the North Sea.
   Hearings on the settlement, which must be approved by the
lenders, the Internal Revenue Sevice, other major creditors and the
bankruptcy court were to begin this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880820-0076 </DOCNO>
