<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Indians 1stld-writethru a0573 08-20 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Indians, 1st ld-writethru, a0573,600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 9 grafs new; pickup 10th graf ``Earlier about'' etc.
^By W. DALE NELSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  Twenty-two members and supporters of
American Indian tribes walked single-file up a seven-mile mountain
road to President Reagan's ranch Saturday, seeking an ``ongoing
dialogue'' on Indian rights.
   The walk was triggered by Reagan's remarks at the Moscow summit
in May, when he spoke of Indians living a ``primitive lifestyle''
and said that, ``Maybe we should not have humored them.''
   Before the march, White House officials met with representatives
of the American Indian Action Group and arranged for Reagan to meet
in Washington with Indian leaders, probably in September.
   ``I would like to thank President Reagan for publicly inviting
us to open up a dialogue,'' Wonono Rubio, a Chumash Indian from
Goleta, Calif., told the group outside the gate of the ranch.
   ``I hope that he keeps the door open and keeps a dialogue as
long as he is president,'' Rubio added. ``One meeting is not going
to solve our problems, and I hope that he keeps it in mind this is
going to be an ongoing dialogue.''
   The walkers marched from Refugio State Beach on the Pacific
Ocean, chanting, beating drums and playing other musical
instruments as they walked up the steep, winding blacktop road.
   Some wore elements of traditional Indian garb as part of their
costumes. One was in the robe of a Buddhist monk. The leader of the
march, Michael Zarate, wore a Mickey Mouse shirt.
   When they reached the ranch, they lined up across the road from
the gate while members designated as elders of various tribes led
them in prayers and songs.
   The walk took about three hours.
   Earlier, about 100 persons assembled at the state park north of
Santa Barbara.
   ``This is going to be a spiritual walk,'' said Michael Zarate, a
leader of the organization. ``I emphasize this, because it is not a
protest march.''
   An announcement of the walk issued on Wednesday had referred to
it as a protest against Reagan's remarks at the Moscow summit in
May, when he said of American Indians: ``Maybe we should not have
humored them in wanting to stay in that kind of primitive
lifestyle. Maybe we should have said, `No, come join us. Be
citizens along with the rest of us'.''
   Zarate said the reference to a protest was ``erroneous'' and the
group had apologized to the White House.
   On Thursday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater telephoned
Zarate and offered to arrange a meeting between the Indians and
White House aides here to set up a session between Reagan and
Indian leaders in Washington.
   On Friday, Zarate said, he met with Fitzwater and M.B. Oglesby,
the deputy White House chief of staff, who said the meeting could
probably be arranged for September.
   ``They also informed us the president would not be able to meet
with us today as we originally requested,'' Zarate said.
   The president and his wife, Nancy, were entertaining old
friends, Mr. and Mrs. Earle Jorgensen and Mr. and Mrs. William
Wilson, at the ranch. The Wilsons and the Jorgensens were giving a
belated birthday party for the first lady, whose birthday was last
month.
   The weather at the ranch, which has generally been sunny since
the Reagans arrived on Tuesday, was cloudy and cool.
   At Refugio Beach, the Indians listened to speakers on
environmental and other issues, and assembled under a eucalyptus
tree for the walk.
</TEXT>
