<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AbductedChildren     08-20 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abducted Children,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Report Urges Paraguay to Help Return Abducted Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. report released Saturday said Paraguay is
not cooperating in efforts to return children of Argentines
detained under that nation's military juntas.
   Referring to Paraguay, the report said it was ``inadmissible and
a matter of serious international concern if a country becomes a
hiding place for kidnappers and illegally appropriated children.''
   The report by Dutch human rights specialist Theo van Boven said
Paraguay, ruled since 1954 by President Alfredo Stroessner's
authoritarian government, should take immediate measures for
repatriating the children.
   At least 9,000 people suspected of being leftist subversives
were seized by Argentine security forces and disappeared during the
``dirty war'' of 1974-81, officials have said. Human rights group
put the number closer to 30,000.
   Van Boven's report said pregnant detainees were placed in secret
detention centers where they gave birth and were separated from
their children.
   His report said many of the children were turned over to
supporters of Argentina's junta through an unofficial adoption
ring, and some of the people who adopted the children fled to
Paraguay when Argentine military rule collapsed. The report said
some of the ``kidnappers'' forged documents to register the
children as their own.
   Argentina's military rule ended in 1983 with the election of
President Raul Alfonsin.
   Van Boven gave no figure for the number of children believed to
be involved. His report said three of 45 such children located to
date were found by the Argentine government and the 42 others were
found by relatives and the Grandmothers of the Plaza Del Mayor, a
private relatives' group.
   That group has said 182 children were taken from their parents
and at least 72 have been repatriated.
   Van Boven said Paraguay denied him entry to investigate the
cases, citing pending judicial inquiries.
   He presented his findings to the U.N. Sub-Commission on
Prevention of Discrimination and Protection of Minorities.
</TEXT>
