<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stld-writethru a0567 08-20 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st ld-writethru, a0567,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: inserts 3 grafs after 13th graf pvs. Pickup 14th graf `Stuart
Spencer'' etc.
^By MERRILL HARTSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate George
Bush gave running mate Dan Quayle a vote of confidence Saturday,
saying he is ``satisfied that there was no impropriety'' in
Quayle's enlistment in the National Guard in 1969.
   Joining Quayle in answering reporters' questions at the Ohio
State Fairgrounds here, Bush defended his selection of the Indiana
senator for the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   ``The premise for this decision was very sound, and the American
people are going to see that, loud and clear,'' he said. ``I've
made a good choice,'' Bush said. ``So, the fact that there is some
flurry out there, and a lot of rumors have to be run down, I don't
see that it's detracting.''
   Bush complained that stories suggesting the young Quayle had
enlisted in the Guard to avoid being drafted at the height of the
Vietnam War ``were greatly overdone.''
   ``I think it will turn out to be a tempest in a teapot,'' he
said.
   Bush complained that the heavy focus on Quayle's National Guard
record by news reporters had interfered with some elements of his
campaign operation during the Republican National Convention in New
Orleans last week.
   ``Please don't judge me by this moment,'' he told reporters.
``We've had to shoot down many unfair rumors. There was this
flurry, you know, ... like bluefish, when they're swimming around,
all in a frenzy. You've made the charges and we felt we had to
answer them.''
   Quayle said he had not deceived the Bush campaign about the
circumstances surrounding his enlistment in the National Guard
nearly 20 years ago.
   ``There's sort of a sentiment out there impugning the motives of
people'' who sign up for the National Guard, he said. ``I told the
Bush campaign there was nothing embarrassing in my military record,
and I'm sticking to it.''
   Quayle said he could not immediately disclose the communications
he might have had with his draft board at the time. But he repeated
that he had asked to have his full military record supplied to him
so that he can release it and better answer questions about it.
   Bush and Quayle on Saturday marched together with their wives,
Barbara and Marilyn, in the Paper Day Parade in nearby West
Carrollton, home of several paper plants.
   Standing on a freshly painted blue stage on a baseball field,
Bush worked a highly partisan crowd into a frenzy with a
restatement of his hard-line opposition to tax increases.
   He said that if Congress tried to get a tax increase past him,
he would ``stare them right in the face, and say what I said in New
Orleans the other night.'' He then paused just along enough to get
large numbers of people in the crowd of 5,000 to 7,500 to join him
in a chorus of, ``Read my lips. No more taxes.'
   Quayle won cheers Saturday from an Oktoberfest crowd of
German-Americans near Cleveland, when he said a Bush administration
would ``see the Berlin Wall come down.''
   Bush and Quayle watched German folk dances and drank beer from
steins at the celebration in Olmsted Township near Cleveland,
putting aside questions that had dogged them earlier in the day
about Quayle's military service.
   Several hundred people jammed into a German-American cultural
center cheered Bush's call for the Soviet Union to demonstrate its
reforms are real by permitting ``a little more freedom in Eastern
Europe.''
   Stuart Spencer, a senior campaign official, said that while he
thought news reporters would continue to ask questions about the
circumstances under which the Quayle joined the National Guard, ``I
think it's behind us. We feel good. We feel upbeat.''
   Quayle has said he thought there was nothing inappropriate about
having a mutual family friend make inquiries in 1969 about the
possibility of the young 22-year-old DePauw University graduate
joining the National Guard.
   ``At least he served,'' said one placard held aloft at the ball
field grounds. Several other signs among the crowd suggested that
Quayle's enlistment in the Guard was a non-issue.
   Bush, emerging from a restaurant here Friday night, said that
Quayle had not misled the campaign about his military record.
``This guy did the honorable thing and told the truth,'' he said.
   Bush campaign press secretary Sheila Tate said Quayle's
question-and-answer session Friday had ``relieved a lot of the
press pressure.'' She said the interruption in getting the Bush
campaign message out was only ``temporary.''
   David Prosperi, a former White House press office official now
at the Interior Department, will join Quayle's campaign as press
secretary on Monday, Ms. Tate said.
</TEXT>
