<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Panama-Americans     08-20 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Americans,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Attacks Against Americans in Panama Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attacks against Americans in Panama have
increased in recent weeks in what U.S. officials see as an effort
to force the United States to lift sanctions against the country,
according to a published report.
   Officials of the State and Defense Departments and the U.S.
Southern Command in Panama say there have been incidents of
beatings, abductions, rape and extortion of American military
personnel and their dependents, The New York Times reported in
Sunday's editions.
   The regime is also refusing to honor visas of some American
officials and has banned mail service at American military and
civilian bases, officials told the newspaper.
   The officials view the incidents as a campaign of harassment by
the regime of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega aimed at pressuring the
United States to lift economic sanctions against Panama, The Times
said.
   The Southern Command, the American military headquarters for
Latin America, has protested the incidents, but officials said the
protests have had no real effect.
   The Times said the Southern Command reported a June incident in
which an enlisted man and his wife were assaulted at gunpoint by a
Panamanian military officer who forced the man into the trunk of
his car, then beat and raped the man's wife.
   In another reported incident, a serviceman who got into an
argument over a parked car with a man believed to be an undercover
Panamanian intelligence officer was taken into a military station
and beaten.
   On August 1, the command reported, four Panamanian military
officers detained a serviceman and his father for 24 hours,
questioned them at gunpoint and robbed them of $300.
   Two days later, an Air Force enlisted woman was sexually abused
by two Panamanian officers, Southern Command officials said.
   About 12,000 U.S. military personnel are based in Panama to
protect the Panama Canal.
   Noriega, chief of the Panamanian Defense Forces and the power
behind the civilian government, is under federal indictment in the
United States on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering.
   The Reagan administration, which continues to recognize the
deposed Eric Arturo Delvalle as Panama's president, has applied
economic sanctions in its effort to oust Noriega. Although the
sanctions have helped push Panama into a depression, Noriega has
refused to step down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880820-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 2320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland 3rdLd-Writethru   08-20 0991</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0579,1017</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pressure for IRA Crackdown After Bomb Kills 8 Soldiers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 2-5 with 8 grafs, report IRA spy may have been
involved. Pick up 6th graf bgng: Northern Ireland Secretary...
Edits pvs grafs 8 and 20 to delete second references to Maginnis
and Hamilton. Inserts one graf after 22nd pvs: The bomb... to
UPDATE with ages of victims, pick up graf 22 pvs: The IRA.... Minor
editing to conform</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OMAGH, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protestant lawmakers on Saturday
demanded that the government begin locking up guerrilla suspects
without trial after a car bomb set by the IRA blew up a busload of
British troops, killing eight.
   Seven soldiers perished in the Friday night blast and one died
Saturday of his wounds. The army said 27 survivors were injured.
   The car bomb blew a crater 6 feet deep in the road and hurled
mutilated bodies into nearby fields.
   It was the deadliest single blow by the IRA against the British
army in Northern Ireland since 1982. It brought to 26 the number of
British military personnel killed in a summer IRA blitz in Northern
Ireland, mainland Britain and continental Europe.
   British Armed Forces Minister Archie Hamilton said in a
television interview there was ``obviously a possibility'' that an
Irish Republican Army spy had managed to penetrate Britain's
security forces and that ``is something that will have to be
investigated.''
   The bus was an unmarked vehicle and supposedly its route and
schedule was secret.
   Ken Maginnis, a Protestant politician, said, ``I believe there
must have been inside information for them (IRA guerrillas) to
pinpoint the attack.''
   ``What I want to know is who informed the terrorists this
busload of men was coming through here,'' he said.
   The IRA asserted responsibility for the attack in a statement to
the Irish media and declared, ``We will not lay down our arms until
the peace of a British disengagement from Ireland is granted to our
nation.''
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King said: ``We have no choice
but to fight and to stand and to defeat the men of violence.''
   At a news conference in Northern Ireland, King said officials
have evidence the explosives were part of several loads of Libyan
armaments reportedly smuggled onto the island in recent years. He
did not elaborate.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher broke off a holiday in Cornwall
and flew to London to meet with Maginnis, one of several Northern
Ireland Protestant members of Parliament who demanded the return of
``selective internment'' _ a controversial policy of locking up
guerrilla suspects without trial, last used in 1975.
   Maginnis, in whose County Tyrone constituency the bombing
occurred, was among the first on the scene. He tearfully described
going to a barn and finding ``a young man gasping his last, just
dying. He had crawled into the most available cover and died over a
bale of hay.''
   With him at the Thatcher meeting was Alan Rainey, who lives near
the scene of the bombing.
   ``I heard screams of agony I shall never forget,'' he said.
``The road was littered with the dead and the dying, they were
scattered and sprayed across the road, behind hedges; and one poor
soul I found wrapped around a telephone pole.''
   Mrs. Thatcher met later with King, Lt. Gen. Sir John Walters,
commander of the British army in Northern Ireland, and Sir John
Hermon, chief constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the
province's police force.
   After two hours of talks King would say only that the possible
reintroduction of the internment policy was still under review.
   The predominantly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British
rule in Northern Ireland and unite the 60 percent Protestant
province with the 95 percent Catholic Irish Republic.
   Lately, the outlawed IRA appears to have shifted tactics away
from attacking local police and militiamen and has concentrated on
army personnel from mainland Britain.
   On June 15, a bomb killed six soldiers in their van in Lisburn,
outside Belfast. Five more have died in IRA attacks this summer in
Belgium, Holland, West Germany and north London.
   Of the nearly 2,700 people killed in Irish-related violence
since 1969, 76 have died this year, compared with 93 in all of
1987. The number of troops killed has gone from three to 25.
   Maginnis, a member of the Protestants' largest party, the
Official Unionists, said of Friday's attack: ``I and the people in
this area know who detonated that bomb. The police know.'' He did
not name those he believed responsible.
   ``Internment is the only alternative to a court system which has
been unable to put murderers behind bars,'' he said. ``I believe
that internment is the only way to deal with these people.''
   Mrs. Thatcher has refused previous internment calls, but Armed
Forces Minister Hamilton said nothing was ruled out.
   Internment was last used between 1971 and 1975 to hold 1,981
people, mostly pro-IRA suspects. It damaged Britain's human rights
record, and moderate politicians warned Saturday its reintroduction
would givr the IRA a propaganda victory.
   The bomb, in a car parked by the road, blew up as the unmarked
bus passed carrying soldiers of the First Battalion of the Light
Infantry to base at Omagh, 50 miles west of Belfast. They had just
flown in from mainland Britain after furloughs and were still in
civilian clothes.
   The army said seven of the dead ranged in age from 18 to 21. It
withheld information on the eighth victim.
   The IRA said it used 200 pounds of plastic explosives.
   The blast, 10 miles from the base, was the deadliest blow to the
army in Northern Ireland since 1982 when a bomb in a pub killed 11
soldiers and six civilians.
   Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's legal political wing Sinn
Fein, said, ``The families of the dead and injured British soldiers
are paying the price of British interference in Irish affairs that
Irish families have paid for decades.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
