<DOCNO> AP880820-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 2316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0568 08-20 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0568,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet Weather Over Eastern Half Of Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7th graf, `Cheyenne, Wyo.,' with one graf to UPDATE with
records.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell across broad sections of the eastern part of the
nation Saturday, including heavy rain in Florida from a tropical
wave, and meteorologists watched two new tropical depressions in
the Atlantic.
   Rain and occasional thunderstorms extended from New Jersey and
southern Pennsylvania through Florida, including the central and
southern Appalachians, and spread into Alabama.
   Rain in Florida came from a tropical wave, a weather system
weaker than the tropical depressions that can grow into hurricanes.
It dumped almost 6{ inches of rain at West Palm Beach on Friday.
The wave moved toward the northwest and up to 4 inches of rain was
expected over parts of central and northern Florida.
   The tropical depressions included one that formed at noon about
150 miles southeast of the southernmost Cape Verde islands, off the
African coast. The second formed Saturday just south of Saint
Vincent in the Windward Islands, which are in the Lesser Antilles.
   Rain also fell on the lower Mississippi Valley, northern Texas
and eastern Oklahoma, and rain was scattered over northern
Minnesota and from southern Nevada across southwestern Wyoming.
   A creek swollen by heavy rain in Indiana swept a car off a
bridge late Friday north of Batesville, and police said Saturday
that a babysitter and a 4-year-old boy were missing. A 7-year-old
girl escaped from the car and was rescued, and a would-be rescuer
was swept downstream before he managed to climb out, state police
said.
   Cheyenne, Wyo., reached 91 degrees, one degree higher than the
record for the date set last year. Sheridan, Wyo., reached 100
degrees, breaking a record of 97 set in 1971.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Bremerton, Fort Lewis and Olympia, Wash., to 99 at Waco,
Texas. The low temperature Saturday morning was 38 degrees at
Truckee, Calif.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from central
Florida across Georgia, Alabama and Mississippi, with rain
scattered from South Carolina across the Virginia coast. Showers
and thunderstorms also were forecast from New Mexico across Arizona
into southern Nevada, and scattered over southern Utah through
northern Colorado plus northwestern Montana.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted over the northern
Atlantic states, the northern Appalachians and the Great Lakes; in
the 70s from Montana across the northern Pacific Coast and along
much of the California coast; in the 90s or near 90 from the
southern Atlantic states across the Gulf of Mexico states, the
lower two thirds of the Mississippi Valley, much of the Plains, and
from the central Pacific Coast across eastern California; near 100
over central Texas; around 105 over the desert Southwest; and in
the 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
