<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Caledonia     08-20 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Caledonia,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pact Signed on Future of New Caledonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-independence groups in New Caledonia and
residents who want the South Pacific archipelago to remain a French
territory reached agreement Saturday on a transitional plan for the
islands' future.
   But militants quickly denounced the accord. Last spring 30
people were killed in political and ethnic violence in New
Caledonia.
   The agreement provides for a referendum on independence in 1998.
During the intervening 10 years the territory would be divided into
three provinces with more autonomy.
   The referendum would be restricted to voters who have lived in
New Caledonia during all of the intervening 10 years.
   Native Melanesians make up only 43 percent of the population.
Separatists claim many settlers _ Europeans, Asians and Polynesians
_ are short-term residents who want to maintain links with France
and outvote them in elections. The ethnic Melanesians, known as
Kanaks, also have had a higher birth rate in recent years and
expect to form the majority again by the end of the century.
   ``This is not the finish today, this is a stage,'' said Louis Le
Pensec, the minister for overseas territories in the French
government of Premier Michel Rocard.
   But Pensec said the agreement was more than could have been
hoped for ``if one remembers the situation the territory found
itself in three months ago.''
   The breakthrough in negotiations following the violence in April
and May came in June when the head of the Kanak Socialist National
Liberation Front, Jean-Marie Tjibaou, and conservative Jacques
LaFleur reached an agreement in principle during talks directed by
Rocard.
   In the Caledonian capital of Noumea, the far-right National
Front issued a statement Saturday saying pro-French leaders who
participated in the talks had committed treason. It said the accord
``will lead the territory irreversibly to independence sooner or
later.''
   Yann Celene Uregei, leader of the separatist United Kanak
Liberation Front that is a member of Tjibaou's alliance, said
Tjibaou had no authority to sign an agreement. He said the proposal
should have been presented first to New Caledonians for debate.
   The plan, drawn up as a law to be presented to the French
National Assembly, will include constitutional changes that must be
approved by French voters in a national referendum to be scheduled
later this year.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
