<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     08-20 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Lawyer Says Swiss May Intercede If Marcos Return Blocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos' lawyer said
Saturday he will ask Swiss authorities not to cooperate with the
government if it refuses to allow the ex-president to return to the
Philippines to face charges he kept money in secret Swiss bank
accounts.
   The government believes Marcos stashed millions of dollars in
Switzerland during his 20-year rule, which ended on Feb. 25, 1986,
when a civilian uprising swept him from office.
   President Corazon Aquino said on Friday she will abide by a
court order approving her ousted predecessor's return from Hawaii,
where he fled after his ouster.
   On Thursday, an anti-graft court said Marcos or his attorney had
the right to be present during testimony of a former government
minister scheduled to give a deposition against Marcos in November.
   Marcos, who is a lawyer, said he would demand his right to come
home and conduct his own defense.
   Marcos lawyer Rafael Recto told reporters he would send copies
of newspaper reports on the court's ruling to Swiss federal and
cantonal authorities who are involved in an investigation into
secret bank accounts the former president allegedly opened in
Switzerland.
   ``If the government should refuse to respect Marcos' human right
to freely return to his own abode, the Swiss government might be
forced to withdraw assistance to the Philippine government,'' Recto
said.
   Recto said that if the government still blocked Marcos' return,
it would be in violation of European human rights covenants, which
the Swiss have signed. Those covenants state that a defendant has
the right to face his accuser personally or with the counsel of his
choice.
   At a news conference Saturday, Armed Forces Chief of Staff Gen.
Renato de Villa said the military command would respect the court's
decision despite security risks.
   ``Certainly, there are some security implications that may come
about with the return of ex-president Marcos to the Philippines at
this time,'' de Villa said. ``But as I said, and I wish to stress,
a court order must be respected and obeyed by everybody.''
   De Villa said Marcos supporters include small numbers of
soldiers who have been dismissed for involvement in previous coup
attempts. But he said they do not have the capacity to topple the
government.
   Others have said Marcos still commands the loyalty of a
considerable number of low- and middle-ranking officers and men.
</TEXT>
