<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Indonesia-Quake     08-20 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indonesia-Quake,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Damages Buildings, Causes Only Minor Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake damaged buildings
and slightly injured eight people in an Indonesian island, a
newspaper reported Friday.
   It was the third tremor to rock parts of this Southeast Asian
country in four days.
   The latest quake hit Manado, the provincial capital of Celebes
island, on Thursday morning, the daily Suara Pembaruan newspaper in
Jakarta reported Friday.
   It quoted sources at a Manado hospital as saying eight people
were treated, all for minor injuries, and released.
   At least 17 buildings were damaged by the quake, which
registered 5.6 on the Richter scale, the newspaper said.
   The country's Meteorological Agency said earlier that the quake
measured 4.8 on the Richter scale.
   Thursday's quake was centered 15 miles northwest of Manado at a
depth of 37 miles, the newspaper said. It was followed by 10 minor
quakes the same day.
   On Monday, an earthquake measuring 5.3 rocked the tourist island
of Bali.
   Another one registering 6 shook eastern Java island and Jakarta
on Wednesday.
   No injuries or major damage were reported in the first two
quakes.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   An earthquake measuring 4 can cause moderate damage, one of
magnitude 5 considerable damage, and a 6 can cause severe damage in
populated areas.
</TEXT>
