<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceProbe     08-20 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Probe,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Almond: Police Corruption Was `Systemic'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corruption among the Providence Police
Department's vice squad is systemic but does not involve
high-ranking officers, a U.S. attorney said Friday.
   Lincoln C. Almond declined to identify the targets of the secret
three-year investigation, nor would he say exactly what misconduct
is alleged. But FBI agent Mike Suddes confirmed the probe concerns
possible misappropriation of drugs and cash seized by Special
Investigations Bureau officers.
   The investigation was kept secret until the FBI demanded
hundreds of pages of documents from the police on Thursday, Almond
said.
   ``Until this year, the investigation was extremely covert,
extremely need-to-know. It was an intelligence-gathering
investigation,'' he said.
   The case involves more than just one or two bad apples, Almond
said.
   ``It would be systemic,'' he said. But he added that
high-ranking officials were not under suspicion.
   ``You're basically talking the street cop,'' Almond said.
   A state law enforcement source who spoke on the condition he not
be identified suggested the investigation may involve a group of
officers who agreed to underreport the cash seized in drug raids
and split the rest among themselves.
   Police Chief Walter J. Clark could not be reached for comment.
An aide said he had left for vacation and would not be back until
Tuesday.
   Some evidence has been presented to a grand jury, but Almond
said indictments are not likely until next year at the earliest.
</TEXT>
