<NOTE>Eds: An AMs separate moved as a0674.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Sir Frederick Ashton</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Frederick Ashton, whose versatility and flair
marked him as one of the world's greatest choreographers, died in
Eye, Suffolk County, Thursday night at age 83.
   Ashton directed the Royal Ballet for seven years and devised
more than 100 ballets, including the comedy ``A Wedding Bouquet''
and ``Ondine,'' a tale of a water nymph.
   He was knighted and admitted to the French Legion of Honor in
1962, awarded a Companion of Honor in 1970, and in 1977 was honored
with the Order of Merit, a distinction limited to 24 members who
are replaced only at death.
   In retirement, Ashton continued to remain active as a consultant
and visitor to both The Royal Ballet and its touring sister
company, the Sadler's Wells Royal Ballet.
</TEXT>
