<DOCNO> AP880820-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AmtrakSettlement     08-20 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amtrak Settlement,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amtrak Agrees To Pay $8.2 Million To Families of Crash Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak has agreed to pay the families of 15
people killed in a January 1987 train crash $8.2 million, on top of
the $58 million settlement agreed to by Conrail two months ago.
   In addition to death claims, Amtrak's and Conrail's settlements
also create a $9 million fund to pay 330 passengers who filed
claims for injuries or distress they suffered because of the Jan.
4, 1987, accident near Chase, Md.
   ``That makes this settlement (on the death claims alone) the
largest group personal injury settlement in the country,'' said
Read K. McCaffrey, an attorney for the victims' families.
   Claims filed by the 16th victim's family were settled earlier.
   ``We think it's a fair settlement and hopefully will put an end
to the uncertainty and the waiting period a lot of people have gone
through,'' Amtrak public affairs director John Jacobsen said
Friday, a day after the settlement offer was made. ``Amtrak feels
it is in some ways as much a victim in this as anyone else is.''
   ``A plan has been formulated where a committee of attorneys
representing (injured victims) will review the claims and recommend
who should get from the $9 million fund,'' McCaffrey said.
   The Amtrak passenger train collided with a Conrail locomotive.
   Ricky L. Gates, the Conrail engineer who was at the controls at
the time of the accident, is serving a five-year prison term for
manslaughter after admitting he'd smoked marijuana shortly before
the crash.
   The total $66.2 million the train companies have agreed to pay
on the death claims means each of the victims' survivors will
receive about $4.5 million, McCaffrey said.
   Under terms of Amtrak's settlement, the railroad did not admit
responsibility for causing the crash or the deaths, McCaffrey said.
</TEXT>
