<DOCNO> AP880820-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FloatingFountain 2ndLd-Writethru a0835 08-20 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Floating Fountain, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0835,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`World's Tallest Floating Fountain' Is Dedicated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT name of fountain in lead and
UPDATE with quote from tourism official, picking up 3rd graf pvs,
`The crowd ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TED M. NATT JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An orchestra played Aaron Copland's
``Fanfare for the Common Man'' Friday night as the 400-foot-high
Louisville Falls Fountain, billed as the world's tallest floating
fountain, debuted before more than 60,000 people.
   ``Paris has its Eiffel Tower. London has Big Ben. Rome has the
Coliseum. And tonight the world-class city of Louisville has the
Louisville Falls Fountain,'' said Mary Ray Oaken, secretary of the
state Tourism Cabinet.
   The crowd lined the banks of the Ohio River as the fountain was
triggered.
   It took 20 minutes for the computer-controlled fountain's 41
jets and red, white, blue and amber lights to complete its program
of patterns, which concludes when the fountain sprays a
fleur-de-lis _ Louisville's official symbol _ about 400 feet above
the river.
   The fountain, on an octagonal barge 39 feet across, is a gift to
the city from Mary and Barry Bingham Sr., who donated $2.6 million
for its construction and maintenance for three years. Bingham,
patriarch of a three-generation media family, died Monday at age 82.
   ``I know that he (Barry Bingham Sr.) is with us tonight in a
spirit of joy and fulfillment,'' Barry Bingham Jr. said.
   Gov. Wallace Wilkinson said he would never see the fountain
without thinking of the elder Bingham and that the fountain would
flow ``as an eternal flame would burn in his memory.''
   Plenty of entertainment was on hand, including dancers, singers,
an orchestra and bands _ the 100th Army Reserve Band, country music
and rock 'n' roll.
   A flotilla of at least 100 boats gathered near the George Rogers
Clark Memorial Bridge, which was closed to vehicular traffic and
was packed with 8,000 to 10,000 people.
   Interstate 64, which skirts the Ohio River at Louisville was
jammed as motorists stopped to watch the fountain dedication,
creating a massive traffic tieup.
   ``I think the whole city is planning a party,'' said John
Richards, executive director of the Mary and Barry Bingham Sr. Fund.
   Electrical engineer Frank Gavuld, who was aboard the barge, said
afterward: ``It ran perfectly. We've had it up to 429 feet, but the
420 feet tonight was right on target.''
   ``I thought it was excellent,'' said Greg Schum of Louisville,
who staked out his spot six hours before the fountain was turned
on. ``It's like fireworks made out of water. It's something the
city can be proud of.''
   The fountain, proposed almost 30 years ago, was built by Pete
Serodino of Chattanooga, Tenn., a marine contractor who has built
other floating fountains around the world. This one sprays the
highest, backers said.
   Plans call for the fountain to operate primarily in the
afternoons and evenings from early spring to early fall.
   When operating fully, it will spout 15,800 gallons of water a
minute, more than the average Louisville household consumes in two
months.
   The fountain is one of five of its kind in the world, according
to the Louisville Central Area, an agency promoting the city.
   Skip Nelson, a member of the development team of International
Fountain Developers in Cincinnati, said the second-largest such
fountain is in Fountain Hills, Ariz. That fountain was rated to run
at more than 500 feet but is actually run at less than 400 feet, he
said. Each of the other four fountains, Nelson said, is a single
jet going straight up into the air.
   But a spokesman for the company that operates the Arizona
fountain says the Louisville fountain's 400-foot advertised height
doesn't come close to theirs.
   The Arizona fountain, first turned on Dec. 15, 1970, is rated at
560 feet, which MCO Properties Inc. spokesman Keith McMahan McMahan
says it reaches any time there's no wind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880820-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AndeanCondors 1stLd-Writethru a0680 08-20 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Andean Condors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Andean Condors to Scout Way for Return of California Condors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with trip under way, picking up
7th graf pvs, `The Andean ....'
^By GEORGE GARTIES</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Andean condors that will serve as scouts
for reintroduction of the gravely threatened California condor into
the wild are headed for temporary pens in a rugged mountain range.
   The 3- and 4-month-old avian pioneers, hatched and reared in
zoos, will spend several weeks in mesh enclosures as scientists
prepare them for their first flights over the dry mountains and
foothills that once supported a thriving population of California
condors.
   The California species _ a black, vulture-like carrion eater
with a wingspan up to 9{ feet _ has dwindled to a mere 28, all in
captivity.
   Two Andean condors from the San Diego Wild Animal Park were
loaded into airline-style animal shipping crates Friday evening for
a 200-mile trip to the secret holding pens in the Los Padres
National Forest, 75 miles northeast of Los Angeles, Tom Hanscom, a
spokesman for the animal park, said in a telephone interview Friday.
   ``They want to arrive and put the birds in their new home in the
dark of night so the birds awaken the next morning thinking they
are in the same place they were before,'' Hanscom said as his crew
was ready to depart at 6:45 p.m. for the six-hour drive.
   The birds were not drugged, but were captured and wrapped in
blankets by familiar handlers, he said.
   ``By moving them in the dark it basically minimizes the
stress,'' Hanscom said.
   A third Andean condor hatched at the Los Angeles Zoo will join
the contingent, along with a fourth, flown in from a U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service center in Patuxent, Md., said Michael Wallace, the
Los Angeles Zoo biologist overseeing the program.
   The Andean birds, all females to prevent breeding in the wild,
will be used to test techniques biologists hope to use _ perhaps as
soon as 1992 _ to begin returning the California condor to nature.
More Andean condors will be added to the test flock later.
   In a $440,000 program overseen by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service, the birds will be taken to a special mesh enclosure,
measuring about 20 feet by 40 feet and 15 feet high, in rugged
territory. The exact spot is secret to deter the curious or the
malicious.
   About November, when the birds are able to fly, they will be
fitted with radio monitoring gear and released. It's expected they
will cover much of the California condor's five-county range, a
land of bare grassy hills dotted with occasional oaks, and rugged,
rocky cliffs and canyons in the mountains that ring the southern
end of the San Joaquin Valley.
   The purpose of the test, Hanscom said, is twofold: To see how
birds hatched in captivity adapt to freedom; and to see if such
birds can learn to fend for themselves in a region without native
birds of their species to serve as examples.
   The program also will help scientists spot such possible hazards
as poison bait illegally left for coyotes or lead shot in animal
carcasses left by hunters, Hanscom said.
   The Andean birds will be captured from the wild when it's time
to release their California cousins, Hanscom said. The first
California birds could be released as early as 1992 if breeding
programs are successful, he said.
   The Andean condor was chosen for the experiment because it is
the closest living relative to the California condor. Though the
Andean species is endangered, they number in the thousands.
   The California condor, North America's largest land bird, once
roamed widely along the West Coast, but its numbers had shrunk to
40 when the Fish and Wildlife Service launched a rescue effort in
1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
