<1ST_LINE>r w PM-VincennesReport Bjt   08-20 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vincennes Report, Bjt,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Errors Caused Shoot-down of Iranian Airbus, Report Concludes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of mistakes by men, not machines, led
to last month's shoot-down by a Navy cruiser of an Iranian
commercial jet, but Iran must share some of the blame, say the
Pentagon's civilian and military leaders and an investigation into
the July 3 incident.
   The U.S. Vincennes fired at the Iranian A-300 Airbus in the
Persian Gulf because the cruiser mistakenly believed the plane was
an Iranian F-14 fighter taking part in an attack in the Strait of
Hormuz, according to the report.
   No Navy personnel will be disciplined, said Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci and Adm. William Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, as they released the report Friday.
   ``I believe that given the operating environment, Capt. (Will
C.) Rogers (III) acted reasonably and did what his nation expected
of him in the defense of his ship and crew,'' said Crowe.
   All 290 people aboard the Airbus were killed when it was shot
down after taking off from Bandar Abbas, which Iran uses as a joint
civilian-military airfield, Crowe noted. The incident came only
minutes after the Vincennes had fired at some Iranian speedboats
which had shot at the cruiser's helicopter.
   ``By any measure, it was unconscionable (for Iran) to ignore the
repeated warnings of the United States and to permit an airliner to
take off from a joint military-civilian airfield and fly directly
into the midst of an ongoing surface action (battle) ...,'' Crowe
declared.
   But Iranian U.N. Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati rejected
U.S. criticism.
   ``Our civil airliner was using an internationally recognized air
corridor, used five times a week by the same captain,'' he said
Friday.
   The Iranian envoy blamed the tragedy on the U.S. Navy's presence
in the Persian Gulf.
   ``One should conclude that the mere presence of such highly
dangerous equipment, which cannot be controlled even by trained
American personnel, is the source of tension,'' he said, and called
for the U.S. fleet to pull out of the gulf.
   The Vincennes is an Aegis-class cruiser, containing the Navy's
most sophisticated air defense system. The investigators concluded,
``The Aegis Combat System's performance was excellent _ it
functioned as designed.''
   But the welter of information provided by Aegis was evaluated by
a crew seeing its first combat, and who had been warned about the
possibility of attacks from Bandar Abbas, the investigators said.
   ``Stress, task fixation and unconscious distortion of data may
have played a major role in this incident,'' concluded the
unclassified, 53-page version of the report released Friday.
   The Iranian plane was picked up by the Vincennes as a radar
contact and the crew then sought proof the plane wasn't part of the
earlier attack, the investigators noted.
   ``The proof never came. Given the time available, the commanding
officer could hardly meet his obligation to protect his ship and
crew and also clear up all of the possible anomalies or
ambiguities,'' said Crowe.
   The United States has apologized and informed Iran it will offer
compensation to the victims' families. Iran, which was scheduled
today to begin a cease-fire in its long war with Iraq, has accused
the United States of deliberately shooting the plane down.
   The investigative report dismissed that charge, stating:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The USS Vincennes did not purposely shoot down an Iranian
commercial airliner. Rather, it engaged an aircraft the commanding
officer ... believed to be hostile and a threat to his ship and to
the (nearby frigate) USS Montgomery.''
   Crowe said that some of the mistakes by the Vincennes' crew
included:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _A conclusion the civilian Airbus was descending rather than
ascending as it approached the Vincennes, implying the plane was
preparing to attack.
   _A conclusion the jetliner had transmitted a radio signal
identifying it as a military aircraft.
   _A report the plane was outside a commercial air corridor
crossing the Persian Gulf.
   Rogers also had a short ``critical decision window,'' the report
states. Only seven minutes passed from the time the ship detected
the airplane taking off until its destruction.
   ``And from the time the CO (Rogers) first became aware of (the
plane) as a possible threat, until he made his decision to engage,
the elapsed time was approximately 3 minutes, 40 seconds,'' the
report states.
   ``The fog of war and those human elments which affect each
individual differently ... are factors that must be considered.
Stress, task fixation and unconscious distortion of data may have
played a major role in this incident.''
   Carlucci said the investigation would lead to a number of
changes in operations, including modifying the devices that display
critical information on approaching targets in the cruisers and
subjecting the operators of the Aegis system to psychological
testing to ensure they are ready for combat.
</TEXT>
