<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeepCave     08-20 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deep Cave,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Help Explore Nation's Third-Deepest Cave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet spelunkers, joining explorers from
the United States and two other nations, have concluded a 10-day
probe of Lechuguilla Cave, the third-deepest cavern in the United
States.
   The cave is in a designated wilderness area of the Carlsbad
Caverns National Park and is known to be at least 21.1 miles in
length. That makes it the deepest cave in New Mexico _ at least
one-third of a mile longer than the surveyed length of the Carlsbad
Caverns.
   The two known deeper caves are in Wyoming.
   Seventy cavers from 18 states, Canada, Switzerland and the
Soviet Union participated in the expedition.
   Project leaders Rick Bridges and Roy Glasier said the group
discovered a considerable amount of ``spongework,'' or passageways,
that add to the cave's complexity.
   Among other findings were a 30-inch gypsum ``flower'' and gypsum
formations resembling yarn and cotton balls.
   The cave has a 90-foot vertical drop at its entrance, according
to park officials. Explorers have known about the cave opening and
entrance room since about 1914. At that time, the cave was mined
for guano, or bat waste.
   Extensive exploration of the cave began four years ago.
</TEXT>
