<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Vincennes-Glance     08-20 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Vincennes-Glance,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Concludes No Negligence In Airbus Shootdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Vincennes Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of the Pentagon's report
on the circumstances of the shooting down of an Iranian commercial
jetliner by the USS Vincennes:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>OPINIONS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The USS Vincennes did not purposely shoot down an Iranian
commercial airliner. Rather, it engaged an aircraft the commanding
officer USS Vincennes believed to be hostile and a threat to his
ship and to the USS Montgomery.
   ``... Iran must share the responsibility for the tragedy by
hazarding one of their civilian airliners by allowing it to fly a
relatively low-altitude air route in close proximity to hostilities
that had been ongoing for several hours...
   ``The downing of Iran Air (Flight) 655 was not the result of any
negligent or culpable conduct by any U.S. Naval personnel
associated with the incident.
   ``... The Aegis Combat System's performance was excellent _ it
functioned as designed ...
   ``Stress, task fixation and unconscious distortion of data may
have played a major role in this incident.
   ``... The USS Vincennes was adequately trained to perform her
missions ...
   ``Iran Air Flight 655, an Airbus 300, was on a normal climb out
of Bandar Abbas and was flying within the established air route,
A-59, from Bandar to Dubai.
   ``... Commercial air, particularly commercial air from Iran, is
at risk in the Persian Gulf as long as hostilities continue in the
area. Unless an aircraft can be visually identified as a
non-threat, any aircraft approaching a U.S. Navy ship could be
considered a threat ....''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>RECOMMENDATIONS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``No disciplinary or administrative action should be taken
against any U.S. naval personnel associated with this incident.
   ``... The CNO (Chief of Naval Operations) direct (that) further
study be undertaken into the stress factors impacting on personnel
in modern warships with highly sophisticated command, control,
communications and intelligence systems, such as Aegis.
   ``... That no changes be made to the existing ROE (rules of
engagement).
   ``... Revise the existing commercial air route structure over
the waters of the Persian Gulf (and require) ... that all flights
climb to at least 25,000 feet over land prior to crossing the Gulf
and begin their descent over land.
   ``... That the Commanding Officer, USS Vincennes, take action as
required to strengthen the AAWC (anti-air warfare controller)
position in the USS Vincennes' CIC (Combat Information Center)
organization.
   ``... If we must operate in a low-intensity conflict and in the
presence of COMAIR (commercial aircraft), we must train to that
environment, real or simulated.''
</TEXT>
