<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AfghanDefector Bjt   08-20 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Defector, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib's Brother Denounces Kabul Regime</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A younger brother of the Soviet-backed leader
of Afghanistan, Najib, says he broke with his brother because he
imposed an ``infamous regime'' on the Afghan people by force of
arms.
   ``He is not being supported by anyone so far as the Afghans are
concerned,'' Sediqullah Rahi told reporters Friday at the State
Department. ``The only support he has is the Soviet Union. He has
tried to impose his regime by way of bayonets.''
   The defection of Rahi, his wife Soraya,and their two young sons
is a propaganda coup for the United States, which has provided
Stinger missiles and other weapons to guerrillas who are at war
with the Afghan and Soviet armies.
   Rahi, 37, who had worked for the Kabul government as a banker,
broke with his brother several years ago and, after serving some
months in prison, fled with his family to the mountains last winter.
   They crossed into Pakistan last month and arrived in Washington
this week where they were granted refuge immediately and given the
protection of bodyguards.
   Rahi said the escape was arranged by Ahmed Shah Massoud, leader
of one of the factions at war with his brother's forces, and that
they had to change getaway cars seven times and houses three times
on their way from Kabul to Massoud's mountain hideaway.
   ``We were constantly under surveillance and they were following
us,'' Mrs. Rahi said. Her bearded husband nodded his concurrence.
   Rahi denounced his brother as ``mentally deranged and the sadist
type.'' He said the government's strength is waning and its morale
is very low.
   The Soviets are in the midst of withdrawing their troops from
Afghanistan where they had backed the Kabul government in an
8{-year war with the rebels.
   Once the Red Army is gone, Rahi said, the government will fall.
``He has tried to impose his regime by way of bayonets,'' Rahi said
of his brother. The rebels ``are the true fighters and defenders of
our country.''
   Rahi said he expected the Soviets to try to rescue elements of
the pro-Moscow government by arranging a coalition with other
Afghan forces. He said Najib might be given haven in the Soviet
Union or another communist country.
   Asked about the Afghan president's claims that his government
can survive without the support of Soviet troops, Rahi said:
``Sheer lies.''
   There are two younger brothers. Tradition binds them to Najib
even if they disagree with him, Rahi said.
   He said the two brothers were trained in Cuba and are working
for the KGB secret police. He said he broke with tradition.
   Mrs. Rahi offered assurances that the rebels were not the sort
of fundamentalists who rule neighboring Iran.
   ``This is something the Afghan people would repel and
repudiate,'' she said.
   Rahi, meanwhile, paid tribute to President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq
of Pakistan, who perished in an airplane crash Wednesday, as a
staunch supporter of the rebels.
   American weapons are funneled through Pakistan to the rebels,
and Pakistan has taken in millions of Afghan refugees.
   Referring to reports of a bomb exploding aboard the presidential
plane, Rahi said, ``This makes one wonder whether this was arranged
by the Kabul regime and India in order to muddy up the situation so
they could take advantage of it for some ulterior motive.''
   He added through an interpreter: ``This could have possibly been
one of the Soviets' intrigues and tricks. Simply, they realized by
trying some diplomatic maneuvers they could not move away Gen. Zia
from his support of the resistance so they decided this could be
the last remedy.''
   Asked if he had evidence to support the allegation, Rahi said:
``We have no evidence. We simply are thinking that because the
Soviets had given Zia warning many, many times that they will take
proper action in due course, if necessary.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
