<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan     08-20 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indians To March to Reagan's Ranch To Protest `Primitive
Lifestyle' Remarks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Indians are going ahead
with a march to President Reagan's ranch to protest his remarks
during the Moscow summit about Indians' ``primitive lifestyle,''
despite White House assurances that the president will meet with
them in Washington.
   The American Indian Action Group and the White House said Friday
that arrangements were being made for such a meeting. The Indians,
who already had planned today's demonstration, said they would
proceed with it because they had made a commitment and people were
traveling distances to participate.
   Reagan told students at Moscow University in May, ``Maybe we
made a mistake in trying to maintain Indian cultures. Maybe we
should not have humored them in wanting to stay in that kind of
primitive lifestyle.''
   The president also suggested that perhaps the government should
have told the Indians, ``No, come join us. Be citizens along with
the rest of us.''
   American Indians were made full citizens by an act of Congress
in 1924.
   The president's remarks were greeted with outrage by many Indian
leaders. Reagan said he would meet with them ``at any time,'' but
the Indians said he failed to respond to letters and telephone
calls from them.
   A member of the American Indian Action Group who said she used
only the name Pilula said that White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater telephoned the group Thursday after plans for the
demonstration had been announced.
   Fitzwater spoke with Michael Zarate, a spokesman for the group,
and said that a letter would follow, Pilula said. Neither Zarate
nor Fitzwater could be reached for comment Friday afternoon.
   Pilula said she assumed Fitzwater's call was prompted by the
announcement of the demonstration, as ``he would not have had any
other reason to call us.''
   ``We did let him know that we would go ahead,'' she said.
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Bob Hall said presidential
aides would meet with the Indians soon, probably while the
president is vacationing at his ranch, to arrange a meeting between
Reagan and the Indians after the president returns to Washington on
Sept. 6.
   ``During his administration, Reagan has never met with Indian
leaders,'' the group said in a statement. ``The remarks he made in
Moscow were his first reference to American Indians in eight
years.''
   The group said more than 200 American Indians were expected to
rally at Refugio State Beach and then walk to the gate of the
president's ranch 20 miles north of Santa Barbara in the Santa Ynez
Mountains.
   The Reagans arrived at the ranch Tuesday from New Orleans, where
the president addressed the Republican National Convention. They
will go to Los Angeles next Tuesday for a five-day stay.
   On the way to Los Angeles, the president will stop at the Marine
Operations Building of the Port of Long Beach to sign a landmark
bill designed to reduce U.S. deficits in world trade. The president
already has indicated that he would sign the bill, and Tuesday is
the deadline for him to do so. The Long Beach setting was chosen
for the ceremony because of the port's role in overseas trade.
   The bill would authorize U.S. negotiators to reach agreements in
the current Uruguay Round of international trade and talks and
would streamline the government system of import curbs, designed to
protect American business and retaliate against trade violations.
</TEXT>
