<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     08-20 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Dismiss Case Against CIA Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former CIA agent Joseph F. Fernandez, a
defendant in the Iran-Contra case, lost a bid to have criminal
charges dismissed on the grounds that his congressional testimony
was used against him improperly by prosecutors.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. on Friday denied a
motion to dismiss the charges against Fernandez that accuse him of
conspiring to ship arms illegally to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels
and concealing the covert operation.
   However, Robinson ordered independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh
to submit by Sept. 23 detailed documentation to show his evidence
against Fernandez was obtained independently of testimony the
former CIA agent gave to the House-Senate committees that
investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   Fernandez, 51, who operated under the pseudonym Tomas Castillo
when he was the CIA station chief in Costa Rica, testified before
the committees under a grant of ``use immunity.'' That meant that
prosecutors cannot use his congressional testimony against him in
the criminal case and cannot obtain evidence based on leads
provided by the immunized testimony.
   Robinson directed prosecutors to turn over to the court a list
of all CIA witnesses who were interviewed after Fernandez gave his
congressional testimony and the basis for the discussion.
   Walsh has denied defense contentions that he relied on
congressional testimony as a source of evidence in the case.
   Fernandez is accused of conspiring to ship arms to the Contras,
who oppose Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, in defiance
of a congressional ban on such aid. Fernandez also is charged with
lying to the CIA and the presidential commission headed by former
Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, that investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   The judge, meanwhile, also ordered Fernandez to comply with the
provisions of the Classified Information Procedures Act, refusing
to declare unconstitutional the statute that requires defendants to
notify the court of any plans to reveal government secrets at trial.
   All defendants in the Iran-Contra case _ Fernandez, former
National Security Council aide Oliver L. North, former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim
and retired Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord _ are to be tried
separately, but no date has been set for any of the trials.
   North and Secord are named as unindicted co-conspirators in the
case against Fernandez.
</TEXT>
