<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     08-20 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Stumping With Bentsen After Whistle-Stop Tour</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top expected</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
was campaigning in Texas today with running mate Lloyd Bentsen, the
man Dukakis increasingly talks about as George Bush defends his
choice to fill the Republican ticket.
   ``Isn't it great to have a Democratic nominee for the vice
presidency whose qualifications have never been questioned by
anyone?'' Dukakis asked rhetorically Friday evening at a rally in
Walnut Ridge, Ark., before he flew here.
   ``The true test of leadership is to be able to make the big
decisions, to choose the best people, and to inspire confidence in
government,'' Dukakis told a crowd of about 2,000 people. ``That's
the test of true leadership.''
   Dukakis has been using lines similar to those since Republican
nominee Bush chose 41-year-old Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle as his
running mate, a selection that was followed quickly by questions
about whether Quayle was qualified to step in as president and
whether he used family influence to get into the National Guard in
1969 to duck combat duty in Vietnam.
   Dukakis and Bentsen appeared together Friday night at a Dallas
fund-raiser and were traveling today to the LBJ Ranch outside
Austin. Dukakis also was to stop in Tennessee on his way home to
Boston.
   The Walnut Ridge stop was the end of a Dukakis whistle stop
train swing Friday through rural Illinois, Missouri and Arkansas.
He drew large crowds at all four depots he visited and was joined
at each by numerous elected officials.
   ``Today we begin that journey to the future,'' Dukakis told the
depot rallies. ``And we begin it in the style of another great
Democratic president, Harry S. Truman,'' he said at Walnut Ridge.
   While he indirectly criticized Bush's selection of Quayle and
the senator's credentials, Dukakis aggressively attacked Bush's
acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention, which the
Democrat said was ``missing a page'' because it failed to address
how a Bush presidency would deal with the budget and trade deficits.
   ``Nowhere in it was there a word about the two most important
economic challenges that will face the next president of the United
States,'' Dukakis said of the Bush speech. ``The first is eight
years of running up budget deficits that have added more to the
national debt than all of the presidents from George Washington to
Jimmy Carter combined. And the second was a record trade deficit.''
   At his second stop Friday, in Bismarck, Mo., Dukakis said Bush
or other Republicans failed to mention the deficits during their
convention because ``they don't know how to deal with it.''
   He labeled attacks by Bush and other Republicans on him the sign
of a ``losing campaign.''
   ``I don't think that you can go to the American people and seek
their support for the presidency if you spend 80 and 90 percent of
your time cutting up the other guy,'' Dukakis said.
   ``The Duke Express'' traveled through the heartland the day
after Bush accepted the Republican presidential nomination.
   The Massachusetts governor at each of the rallies mentioned his
state's unemployment rate has been about 3 percent for several
years while the jobless rates in each of the towns he visited was
near 10 percent. Dukakis blamed Reagan administration policies
that, he said, fueled prosperity in some regions but ignored and
exacerbated economic distress in others.
   ``They may be satisfied, but we aren't,'' Dukakis said. ``We can
do a lot better.''
   Dukakis repeatedly mentioned the deficits, a lack of affordable
housing, the Pentagon procurement scandal and the stewardship of
former Attorney General Edwin Meese III. He said Republicans ducked
those issues at their convention.
   Dukakis led the crowds in the refrain ``not a single word from
the Republicans'' after mentioning each of those issues.
   The candidate drew laughs from reporters in Bismarck when he
joked about criticism from Republicans that Dukakis and his wife,
Kitty, show too much affection in public.
   ``It's true that Democrats sleep in double beds and Republicans
prefer twins,'' he said. ``That's why there are more Democrats.''
   Bentsen, meanwhile, campaigning across his home state, said
Bush's convention address didn't deal with ``how the Republicans
are going to face some of the real problems'' of America.
   For example, he said, ``If you're worried about health care for
the elderly or for children, we didn't hear any of the specifics
about how those concerns are going to be met.''
   ``Let's face some facts. What we saw was the Republicans putting
on a convention for the Far Right,'' Bentsen said. ``They had a
Mardi Gras for the Moral Majority.''
</TEXT>
