<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 4thLd-Writethru a0850 08-20 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0850,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Koreas End Talks Without Major Progress, Plan More Monday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs with talks over, more planned. Pick up 3rd
pvs, `The five-member...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South and North Korean delegates ended a
second day of talks Saturday but failed to make major progress on
clearing the way for full-scale talks on a non-aggression pact and
sharing the Olympic Games.
   They agreed to a third meeting Monday.
   The two sides appeared far apart on all main issues as lawmakers
from each side met in the South Korean pavilion at the truce site
straddling the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas. On
Friday, delegates met in the North Korean pavilion.
   The five-member delegations shook hands and cracked jokes before
beginning negotiations, but observers described the mood as guarded.
   Chief South Korean delegate Park Joon-kyu, in an opening speech,
offered a number of minor concessions on the terms for holding
joint parliamentary talks. The changes were basically rewordings of
proposals and the South did not revise its main positions.
   North Korea's delegates said the South was making discussions
more complex without making progress.
   ``There is nothing new in your proposal,'' said chief North
Korean delegate Chon Kum Chol.
   The North Korean delegation continued to press for full-scale
parliamentary talks on a non-aggression pact and allowing the North
to co-host the Olympic Games that begin Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   South Korea showed no willingness to back down on its position
that the only solution for the Olympics was for the North to
participate in the Games in Seoul, but that co-hosting was
impossible.
   The meeting on Friday also ended with no progress. Before the
sides met, Park said he was optimistic an agreement could be
negotiated, but after the working meeting, he rated chances for
holding full talks at ``50-50.''
   Park said he needs ``a little bit of glasnost'' _ using Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's catchword for openness _ from North
Korea before agreeing to full talks on easing their 40-year rivalry.
   The Korean peninsula was divided north and south at the end of
World War II in 1945. The nations technically are still at war
since no peace treaty was signed after the Korean War of 1950-53.
   North Korean has called for a joint meeting of the two
countries' parliaments, involving nearly 1,000 lawmakers, to
discuss the Olympics and a non-aggression pact.
   South Korea sought to call a ``representative meeting'' of 20
lawmakers from each side, whose main business would be to fix the
agenda and work out other details for full talks.
   The North Koreans also proposed that both legislatures make a
joint declaration of non-aggression, bypassing their governments.
   Seoul maintains that military matters must be handled by the
executive branches of the two governments. Park said the North
Koreans are trying to avoid dealing with President Roh Tae-woo, and
get 42,000 U.S. troops withdrawn from South Korea.
   Chief North Korean delegate Chon Kum Chol reinterated his
country's demand to share in the Olympics. He said the event ``is
not a simple sports game but a serious political problem which will
decide the destiny of the Korean people.''
   Park said the only solution was for North Korea to participate
in the Games. He said South Korea would keep the door open for
North Korea's participation, but noted the deadline for entries is
Sept. 2.
   North Korea is demanding to be a o-host at the Olympics to stave
off a major political defeat. Both sides claim to be the sole
legitimate government of Korea. South Korea sees its selection to
be host of the Olympics as international recognition of its claim.
   The International Olympic Committee says North Korea cannot be a
co-host because the Games are awarded to a single city. South
Korean authorities say North Korea may use terrorism to try to
disrupt the Olympics.
   Sporadic talks between the two sides since the early 1970s
failed to make progress on easing hostilities. The last talks
collapsed in January 1986 when North Korea pulled out to protest
annual South Korean-U.S. military exercises.
</TEXT>
