<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArsonRecord     08-20 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arson Record,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Admits Setting 62 Fires In Three Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KONGSBERG, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they arrested a man who
admitted setting 62 fires in three years _ an arson record.
   No one was injured in the fires, which caused an estimated $15
million damage. The 36-year-old man told investigators he used
paper and a lighter to start the fires, always on weekends.
   ``To us, it seems that the man had a need to fill up his
weekends with excitement,'' police spokesman Bjoern Haneborg said
Friday. The man was not identified in keeping with Norwegian police
regulations.
   The first fire was in the man's hometown of Sandefjord, 50 miles
south of Oslo on May 12, 1985. The last one was in nearby
Holemstrand on June 13, police said.
   According to police, he set a Norwegian arson record. A man who
set 44 fires had been on record as the country's worst arsonist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
