<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0766 08-20 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0766,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 17th graf, ``Serial: xxx '' to CORRECT serial number in
quote</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush and Quayle Commence Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly crowned presidential nominee
George Bush kicked off his general election campaign in the heart
of middle America, but the star-spangled kickoff rally was marred
by running mate Dan Quayle's continuing defense of his military
record.
   Bush and Quayle came to the senator's hometown to launch their
campaign, and a crowd of some 8,000 to 10,000 flag-waving and
cheering townspeople greeted them. But not long after the pair
delivered standard campaign-style speeches, Quayle was off to the
side of the Huntington County Courthouse lawn, answering reporters'
questions.
   Quayle, in a give-and-take session that had been set up by the
Bush organization and piped to the crowd by loudspeaker system,
combatively defended his 1969 decision to join the National Guard
during the height of the Vietnam War.
   Commenting on persistent reports that he used family connections
to win a spot on a National Guard unit roster, Quayle said, ``I can
assure you that I asked no one to break any rules, and that I broke
no rules at all.''
   ``I was on active duty for six months,'' he said. ``I could have
been called to Vietnam, as many Indiana units were, and if I had
been called, I would have gone.''
   Members of the crowd, witnessing an extraordinary confrontation
between a high-profile public figure and reporters, booed lustily
when Quayle was asked repeatedly about his motives for joining the
Guard.
   During his speech to the crowd here, Bush said he thought he
would beat historical odds against vice presidents seeking the
presidency.
   He said that at the end of Thursday night's acceptance speech,
``I just couldn't help but think that old Martin Van Buren was up
there giving me the high-five sign,'' he said. Van Buren was the
last vice president to win the top job, and that was over 150 years
ago.
   Bush and Quayle appeared together in New Orleans earlier Friday
at a meeting of the Republican National Committee.
   The newly minted ticket got well wishes from party figures
before flying to Quayle's home state of Indiana.
   Quayle continued to poke fun at the uproar surrounding reports
of his National Guard involvement during his appearance before the
RNC.
   ``Marilyn (Quayle's wife) and I are just getting used to how we
are supposed to conduct ourselves on the campaign trail,'' he said.
   The 41-year old senator strode to the podium following Bush's
speech and said, ``I think I now know how to introduce myself.''
   He came to attention, snapped his heels together and said:
   ``Name: Dan Quayle.''
   ``Rank: sergeant.''
   ``Serial number: 303 50 4096.''
   ``Status: In the National Guard six years and proud of it.''
   Bush and Quayle were in high spirits the morning after the
conclusion of the Republican National Convention, and both seemed
eager to proceed with what Bush called ``the countdown phase.''
   The pair scheduled campaign trips over the next two days to
Dayton, Cleveland and Columbus, Ohio, and to the Illinois State
Fair in Springfield.
   In a brief talk to the Republican Party leaders before leaving
New Orleans, Bush said the convention amounted to another
``shifting of gears'' in the campaign, and said that now ``we're
coming to the beginning of the end. I'm convinced we're going to
win.''
   Bush said he thought the convention had helped him get his
message to the American people and ``beyond the filters'' that
obscure his points. He evidently was referring to fact that his
speech was broadcast live.
   He said his basic campaign message will be constituted in part
by emphasis on maintaining world peace and security and the other
half will focus on ``enlarging the prosperity so that everyone
benefits.''
   ``We have a good message, it's an upbeat message,'' he said.
Saying most elections hinge on the pocketbook issues, Bush said the
coming campaign gauge ``the innate optimism aand pessimism of the
American people.''
   Bush said that ``we have not yet captivated'' the kinds of
public opinion poll numbers that would be reflected by a belief by
people that they're better off than they were eight years ago.
   Bush saluted Quayle as ``that young spirit'' who relates to the
``changing decade we're moving into.''
</TEXT>
