<FILEID>AP-NR-08-20-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Bandits Bjt   08-20 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bandits, Bjt,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Turned Down Feds' Elite Anti-Terror Squad In Hostage Ordeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government says it offered
state authorities the use of an elite anti-terrorist squad after
two bank robbers set off on a murderous highway rampage, but the
crack unit was never used.
   A young woman, a 15-year-old boy and a police officer died
during the 54-hour ordeal that began with a bank robbery, escalated
into a bus hijacking and ended with a bloody gunfight on a highway
near Bonn.
   Criticism of the state government's handling of the case
heightened considerably on Friday, one day after two men and a
woman were arrested.
   Michael Butz, spokesman for the federal Interior Ministry, told
reporters the country's elite GSG-9 anti-terrorist force was
offered to North Rhine-Westphalia state officials to help end the
crisis.
   Instead, North Rhine-Westphalia officials dispatched a police
commando unit. The commandos rammed the getaway car, and a gun
battle ensued that resulted in the death of one of two hostages.
   Asked if the federal government regrets that the GSG-9 was not
used, Butz replied only: ``The legal situation in which the states
have responsibility for police deployments must be respected.''
   The GSG-9 rescued 86 passengers held by terrorists on a
Lufthansa airliner on Oct. 13, 1977 at Mogadishu, the capital of
Somalia.
   Some politicians criticized North Rhine-Westphalia officials for
not making use of the GSG-9, which stands for
Grenzschutzgruppe-Unit 9, or Federal Border Guard Troops-Unit 9.
   State officials defended their actions during the ordeal, which
began Tuesday when two men robbed a bank in the northwestern town
of Gladbeck. Authorities gave them a getaway car, and they fled
with two hostages.
   The gunmen surfaced Wednesday in Bremen, 125 miles to the
northeast, where they seized a bus with about 30 people aboard.
   Most of the ordeal occurred in Bremen and in North
Rhine-Westphalia state, but the gunmen also drove the bus across
the border into the Netherlands, then returned to West Germany in a
car provided by Dutch authorities.
   A federal official, Education Minister Juergen Moellemann, said
North Rhine- Westphalia Interior Minister Herbert Schnoor and Bernd
Meyer, interior minister for the city of Bremen, should resign.
   ``It is totally unconceivable why actions were not taken sooner
(to stop the bandits),'' Moellemann was quoted as saying in the
mass-circulation Bild newspaper.
   Schnoor said he takes ``political responsibility'' for North
Rhine-Westphalia law officials' handling of the crisis, but he
rejected allegations they bungled the job.
   Meanwhile, officials said they are certain that hostage Silke
Bischof, 18, was killed by one of the bank robbers and not by
police during Thursday's shootout.
   Police identified the gunmen as Dieter Degowski, 32, and
Hans-Juergen Roesner, 31, and their alleged female accomplice as
Marion Irma Loeblich, 34.
   A second hostage in the getaway car, identified by the ZDF as
18-year-old Ines Voitelle, was grazed by a bullet on the back while
gunman Roesner was shot in the thigh during the police shootout.
   An Italian teen-ager, Emanuele de Giorgi, was shot to death
Wednesday night after the busload of hostages stopped at a highway
rest area near Bremen.
   The Frankfurt newspaper Abendpost on Friday said the 15-year-old
was killed by the gunmen while trying to protect his little sister
from them.
   A police officer also died in a car crash while pursuing the
bandits toward the Netherlands.
   All the hostages but Ms. Bischof and Ms. Voitelle either escaped
or were freed after the bus arrived in the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
